s|publisher=Sears Brands|accessdate=31 July 2011}}</ref>\n*Companion \u2013 Tools\n*[[Conqueror Records]] \u2013 Record Label\n*[[Craftsman (tools)|Craftsman]] \u2013 Tools (sold to [[Stanley Black and Decker]]; still sold in Sears and other stores, under licensing deals, but no longer an exclusive brand)\n*Dashmate \u2013 Automobile radios and tape players\n*[[David Bradley (plowman)|David Bradley]] \u2013 Farm machinery and equipment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/davidbradley.htm |title=David Bradley: 1910\u20131966 |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*[[Dean Witter Reynolds]] \u2013 Financial services\n*Dunlap \u2013 Tools\n*Economy \u2013 Iceboxes, fountain pens, sewing machine cabinets, gasoline engines, portable saw rigs, farm equipment, cream separators<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/economy.htm|title=Economy: 1902-1947|website=www.searsarchives.com}}</ref>\n*Free Spirit \u2013 Bicycles\n*Gold Bond \u2013 Footwear\n*Goolagong \u2013 Clothing\n*Handiman \u2013 Line of tractors and walk-behind equipment<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.farmcollector.com/tractors/sears-handiman-zmlz16marzhur |title=Rediscovering the Sears Handiman Line \u2013 Tractors |last=Moore |first=Sam |date=March 2016 |website=Farm Collector |language=en |access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref>\n*Harmony House \u2013 Interior decorating products<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/harmonyhouse.htm |title=Harmony House: 1940\u20131968 |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*Hearthside \u2013 Rug looms and quilting frames\n*Hercules \u2013 Work clothing, appliances, insurance, sewage systems, [[letter jackets]], fire extinguishers, heavy-duty coveralls, home heating systems<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/hercules.htm |title=Hercules: 1908\u20131965 |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*Hillary \u2013 Camping and outdoor gear\n*Homart \u2013 Heating and cooling systems, plumbing supplies, electrical supplies, kitchen cabinets, building supplies\n*[[J. C. Higgins]] \u2013 Sporting goods, camping<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/jchiggins.htm |title=J.C. Higgins: 1908\u20131964 |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*Kromedge \u2013 Sawblades, dadoes, moldering heads, router bits\n*LXI \u2013 Stereo audio components and systems\n*[[Oxford Records]] \u2013 Record Label\n*Penske \u2013 Automotive testing tools\n*Permanex \u2013 Blow-molded polyethylene tool storage cases, gas cans\n*Personal Identity - teen clothing and footwear\n*Pilgrim \u2013 Clothing<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/pilgrim.htm |title=Pilgrim: 1905\u20131964 |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*PROformance \u2013 Stereo audio components and systems (replaced LXI)\n*Sears Video Arcade \u2013 In-house version of [[Atari]] in the early 1980s (discontinued in favor of the actual Atari systems)\n*Seventeen \u2013 Young women's clothing (part of a 2014 license deal with [[Seventeen (American magazine)|the magazine of the same name]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hearst.com/newsroom/seventeen-launches-new-clothing-line-with-sears |title=Seventeen Launches New Clothing Line with Sears |publisher=Hearst Corporation |date=August 26, 2014 |accessdate=November 5, 2017}}</ref>\n*Silvertone \u2013 Stereos, televisions, musical instruments<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/silvertone.htm |title=Silvertone: 1915\u20131972 |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*[[Silvertone Records (1916)|Silvertone Records]] \u2013 Record Label\n*[[Supertone Records]] \u2013 Record Label\n*Ted Williams Brand \u2013 Sporting goods\n*Tower \u2013 Cameras, photo supplies, office equipment\n}}\n\n===Sponsorships===\nThe company sponsors, through the Sears Auto Centers, the Formula Drift Darren McNamara Sears/Falken Saturn Sky drift car. It sponsored the [[NASCAR]] [[Camping World Truck Series|Truck Series]], using the Craftsman brand as the title sponsor, from the series' inception in the [[1995 NASCAR SuperTruck Series presented by Craftsman]] to the [[2008 NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series|2008 season]], when the agreement ended.<ref>[http://www.kansascity.com/news/breaking_news/story/388059.html \"Craftsman Dropping Sponsorship of NASCAR Truck Series\"]. ''[[The Kansas City Star]]''. December 4, 2007.</ref> Craftsman tools remain the official tools of NASCAR. The company sponsored the television series ''[[Extreme Makeover: Home Edition]]''. It sponsors and currently has naming rights to the [[Sears Centre]], an 11,000-seat multi-purpose family entertainment, cultural and sports center, constructed in 2006 in Hoffman Estates. The company also underwrote the [[PBS]] television series ''[[Mister Rogers' Neighborhood]]'', under the name The Sears-Roebuck Foundation from the show's premiere in 1968 until 1992. It sponsored the #10 [[Gillett Evernham Motorsports]] car of Scott Riggs for the September 2, 2007, running of the [[Sharp AQUOS 500]] at [[California Speedway]] through its Sears Auto Center branch. However, Riggs failed to qualify for the event.\nIn 2016, Craftsman became the title sponsor of the World Racing Group, World of Outlaws Sprint car racing series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woosprint.com/sponsors|title=World of Outlaws Craftsman Sprint Car Series \u2013 Sponsors|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Employee relations==\n[[File:Sears Centro Historico.jpg|thumb|Sears building in the [[Edificio La Nacional]] building in Mexico City, across from the [[Palacio de Bellas Artes]].]]\nSears has struggled with employee relations. One notable example was the shift in 1992 from an hourly wage based on longevity to a base wage (usually between US$3.50 and US$6 per hour) and commissions ranging from 0.5% to 11%. Sears claimed the new base wage, often constituting a substantial (up to 40%) cut in pay, was done \"to be successful in this highly competitive environment\".<ref>\"600-plus Sears jobs to be cut\", ''Chicago Tribune'', February 13, 1992</ref>\n\nIn early October 2007, Sears cut commission rates for employees in select departments to anywhere from 0.5% to 4% but equalized the base wage across all Home Improvement and Electronics departments. In 2011, commission rates on non-base items were cut by 2% in the electronics department. In late 2009, the commission on sales of \"base items\" from the electronic department was cut to 1%. As of 2017, appliances is the only remaining department where compensation is based entirely on commission. Other departments give a base pay plus commission. In many stores, jewelry department associates receive a low base salary with 1% commission on their sales.\n\nIn March 2019, Sears claimed that it was ending life insurance benefits for an undisclosed number of its 90,000 retirees. A few months earlier the company handed out over $25 million in bonuses to executives.<ref>{{cite news |last= Folley|first=Aris|date=March 30, 2019|title=Sears cutting life insurance benefits for up to 90,000 retirees: report|url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/436593-sears-cuts-life-insurance-benefits-for-up-to-90000-retirees|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|location= |access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref> This key Sears Retiree Benefit was worth between $5,000 and $15,000 for most of the pool (29,000) of eligible retired employees.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mooney|first=John|date=July 30, 2019|title=Sears Retiree Benefit|url=https://choiceseniorlife.com/2019/07/what-do-you-do-when-sears-cancels-your-life-insurance-policy/ |website=ChoiceSeniorLife.com}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2019, former Sears Holdings chairman and CEO Eddie Lampert, months after purchasing the remains of Sears from the holding company, threatened not to pay out the $43 million in pension payments<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/29/business/sears-severance/index.html|title=Sears' owner wants to get out of paying $43 million in severance to former employees|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref> owed to 90,000 former Sears and Kmart employees and retirees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/government-fears-eddie-lampert-would-wipe-out-sears-pension-plans|title=Government fears Eddie Lampert would wipe out Sears' pension plans|last=|first=|date=February 1, 2019|work=|access-date=}}</ref> A ''[[Forbes]]'' editorial pointed out that [[Steven Mnuchin]], [[Secretary of the Treasury]], was a board member of Sears Holding until 2016, and is presently one of three directors of the [[Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation]], which manages administration of pensions for defunct or bankrupt businesses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/warrenshoulberg/2019/06/03/the-shameless-sears-world-of-eddie-lampert-continues/#296430171fd6/|title=The Shameless Sears World Of Eddie Lampert Continues|last=|first=|date=June 3, 2019|work=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"50\">\nFile:Sears, Robuck & Co. letterhead 1907.jpg|Letterhead logo 1907\nFile:Sears logo 1966-1984.svg|Logo 1963\u201384\nFile:Sears1984.png|1984\u201394\nFile:Sears logo 1994-2004.svg|1994\u20132004 (still used in [[Sears Mexico|Mexico]])\nFile:SearsLogo.svg|2004\u201310 (2004\u201316 in Canada)\nFile:Sears logo 2010-present.svg|2010\u201320\n</gallery>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile: Sears Auto Center.jpg|Sears Auto Center at [[Steeplegate Mall]] in [[Concord, New Hampshire]]. Both the Auto Center and the main Sears store at this location closed in February 2020.\nFile:2006 Sears Hawthorn Center.jpg|Exterior of the Sears at the [[Westfield Hawthorn]] in [[Vernon Hills, Illinois]]. This location closed in August 2018.\nFile:1.8.09ParamusParkMallByLuigiNovi3.jpg|Mall entrance to the former Sears at [[Paramus Park]] in [[Paramus, New Jersey]].\nFile:Searsessentials.jpg|Exterior of the Sears Essentials in [[Palm Springs, Florida]] (reopened as Sears Outlet and closed)\nFile: Sears grand tarentum.JPG|2013 photo of the mall entrance to the Sears Grand at [[Pittsburgh Mills]] in [[Tarentum, Pennsylvania]]. This Sears closed in January 2015.\nFile: Sears Parts Repair Brooklyn.JPG|Exterior of the Sears Parts & Repair Store in [[Brooklyn, Ohio]]\nFile: Sears Ciudad de Mexico.jpg|Exterior of the Sears in [[Mexico City]].\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Chicago|Illinois|Companies}}\n*[[Gala-Sears]] \u2013 defunct Chilean unit\n*[[Sears Canada]] \u2013 defunct Canadian unit\n*[[Sears (Mexico)]] \u2013 Mexican unit held by [[Grupo Carso]]\n*[[Sears plc]] \u2013 former UK company unrelated to U.S. retailer\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*Chang, Myong-Hun, and Joseph E. Harrington Jr. \"Organizational structure and firm innovation in a retail chain.\" ''Computational & Mathematical Organization Theory'' 3.4 (1998): 267\u2013288. compares Sears' Robert E. Wood with Montgomery Ward's Sewell Avery [http://s3.amazonaws.com/academia.edu.documents/39033/he4fl950p7t1t8hyaxg.pdf?AWSAccessKeyId=AKIAJ56TQJRTWSMTNPEA&Expires=1481354969&Signature=EqeQe%2BmYvLI4vf0ZYLM4s3BF%2FZU%3D&response-content-disposition=inline%3B%20filename%3DPDF_Copy.pdf online]{{dead link|date=June 2017}}\n* {{Cite news |last1=Creswell |first1=Julie |title=The Incredible Shrinking Sears |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2017-08-11 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/11/business/the-incredible-shrinking-sears.html |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |df=mdy-all }}\n*Emmet, Boris, and John E Jeuck. ''Catalogs and Counters: A History of Sears, Roebuck, and Company'' (1950), the standard scholarly history\n*Israel, Fred L. ''1897 Sears, Roebuck, and Co Catalogue 100th Anniversary Edition, ''Philadelphia: Chelsea House Publishers, 1968.\n*Katz, Donald R. ''The Big Store: Inside the Crisis & Revolution at Sears'' (1987)\n*Worthy, James C. ''Shaping An American Institution: Robert E. Wood and Sears, Roebuck'' (1986)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sears, Roebuck and Company}}\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{Sears Holdings}}\n\n[[Category: Companies based in Cook County, Illinois]]\n[[Category: Department stores of the United States]]\n[[Category: Former components of the Dow Jones Industrial Average]]\n[[Category: Hoffman Estates, Illinois]]\n[[Category: Lists of brands by company|Sears]]\n[[Category:Mail-order retailers]]\n[[Category: Manufactured home manufacturers]]\n[[Category: Online marketplaces of the United States]]\n[[Category: Sears Holdings]]\n[[Category:1886 establishments in Minnesota]]\n[[Category: American companies established in 1886]]\n[[Category: Retail companies established in 1886]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Department store chain in the United States}}\n{{About|the chain of department stores|its former parent company|Sears Holdings|its current parent company|Transform Holdco LLC|the defunct Canadian subsidiary|Sears Canada|other uses|Sears (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Sears, Roebuck and Company\n| logo = Sears 2020 logo.jpg\n| caption = \n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry = Retail\n| fate = \n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1892}}<br>[[Chicago]], Illinois, U.S.\n| founders = [[Richard Warren Sears]]<br>[[Alvah Curtis Roebuck]]\n| defunct =\n| location_city = [[Hoffman Estates, Illinois|Hoffman Estates]], [[Illinois]]\n| location_country = U.S.\n| locations = <200 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/05/business/sears-kmart-store-closings-trnd/index.html|title=What's left of Sears and Kmart|first=Jordan |last=Valinsky|website=[[CNN]]|date=September 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_served = {{Plainlist|\n*[[United States]]\n*[[Puerto Rico]]\n*[[Bermuda]] \n}}\n| products = {{flatlist|\n*Clothing\n*footwear\n*bedding\n*furniture\n*jewelry\n*beauty products\n*appliances\n*housewares\n*tools\n*toys\n}}\n| revenue = {{decrease}} [[United States dollar|US$]]13.8 billion (2016)<ref name=\"2016form10k\">{{cite report |author=Sears Holdings Corporation |title=2016 Form 10-K, Sears Holding Corporation |url=https://searsholdings.com/docs/investor/SHC_2016_Form_10-K.pdf |publisher=United States Securities and Exchange Commission |format=pdf |year=2016 |page=41 |accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref>\n| operating_income = {{decrease}} \u2212{{US$}}1.448 billion (2016)<ref name=\"2016form10k\"/>\n| parent = [[Transform Holdco LLC]]<ref name=\"businesswire.com\">{{Cite press release|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190211005792/en/ESL-Investments-Completes-Acquisition-Sears-Holdings%E2%80%99-Assets|title=ESL Investments Completes Acquisition of Sears Holdings' Assets|date=February 11, 2019|website=[[Business Wire]]}}</ref>\n| subsid = [[#Subsidiaries|''See below'']]\n| homepage = {{URL|sears.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Sears, Roebuck and Company''', colloquially known as '''Sears''', is an American chain of [[department store]]s founded by [[Richard Warren Sears]] and [[Alvah Curtis Roebuck]] in 1893, and was reincorporated by Richard Sears and [[Julius Rosenwald]] in 1906. Formerly based at the [[Willis Tower|Sears Tower]] in [[Chicago]] and currently headquartered in [[Hoffman Estates, Illinois]], the operation began as a [[mail order]]ing catalog company and began opening retail locations in 1925. The first location was in Chicago, Illinois.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Emmet |first1=Boris |last2=Jeuck |first2=John |title=Catalogues and Counters: A History of Sears, Roebuck and Company |url=https://archive.org/details/cataloguescounte0000emme |url-access=registration |date=1950 |publisher=The University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago & London |isbn=0226207102 |page=[https://archive.org/details/cataloguescounte0000emme/page/341 341] }}</ref> In 2005, the company was bought by the management of the American [[big box]] chain [[Kmart]], which formed [[Sears Holdings]] upon completion of the merger.\n\nThrough the 1980s, Sears was the largest retailer in the United States; [[Walmart]] and [[Kmart]] surpassed Sears in sales in 1990.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1991-02-15/business/9101080852_1_wal-mart-stores-supercenter-stores-hypermart-usa-units |title=1990 Sales Lift Wal-mart Into Top Spot |publisher=Sun Sentinel |date=February 15, 1991 |accessdate=January 15, 2014}}</ref>  In 2018, Sears was the 31st-largest retailer in the United States.<ref name=\"stores.org\">{{cite web |url=https://stores.org/stores-top-retailers-2017/ |title=2017 Top 100 Retailers |publisher=STORES.org |date= |accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref>  After several years of declining sales, Sears' parent company filed for Chapter 11 [[bankruptcy]] on October 15, 2018.<ref name=\"nyt1\">{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/14/business/sears-bankruptcy-filing-chapter-11.html |title= Sears, the Original Everything Store, Files for Bankruptcy |author= Michael Corkery |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date= October 14, 2018}}</ref>  Sears announced on January 16, 2019 that it had won its bankruptcy auction and would shrink and remain open with 425 stores.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/sears-to-stay-open-after-edward-lampert-prevails-in-bankruptcy-auction-11547636823|title=Sears to Stay Open, After Edward Lampert Prevails in Bankruptcy Auction|last=Kapner|first=Suzanne|date=2019-01-16|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-01-16|last2=Rizzo|first2=Lillian|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Nevertheless, the trend of Sears and Kmart store closures continues, with 182 stores expected to remain open by February 2020.<ref name=\"182 stores\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/sears-to-close-96-more-stores-kmart-list-sears-transformco-2019-11|title=Sears is closing 96 more stores, leaving only 182 stores left in the US . Here's the full list of the ones closing.|last=Ciment|first=Shoshy|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-12-29 |date=November 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Mail order catalog===\n[[File:Richard Sears.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Richard Warren Sears]]]]\n\nIn 1863, Richard Warren Sears was born in [[Stewartville, Minnesota]] to a wealthy family, which moved to nearby [[Spring Valley, Minnesota|Spring Valley]].<ref name=SVMuseum>[http://www.springvalleymnmuseum.org/wildersears.html Richard Sears], Spring Valley Methodist Church Museum, Accessed January 17, 2011.</ref> In 1879, Sears' father died shortly after losing the family fortune in a speculative stock deal.<ref name=SVMuseum/> Sears moved across the state to work as a railroad station agent in [[Redwood Falls, Minnesota|North Redwood]], as well as in [[Minneapolis]]. \n\nWhile in North Redwood, a jeweler refused delivery on the shipment of watches. Sears purchased them, then sold them at a low price to the station agents and made a profit. He started a mail-order watch business in Minneapolis in 1886, calling it \"R.W. Sears Watch Company.\" Within the first year, he met Alvah C. Roebuck, a watch repairman. In 1887, Sears and Roebuck relocated the business to Chicago; later that year, the R.W. Sears Watch Company published Richard Sears' first mail-order catalog, offering watches, diamonds, and jewelry. \n[[File:Julius Rosenwald 02.jpg|thumb|170px|Julius Rosenwald]]\nIn 1889 Sears sold his business for [[US$]]100,000 (${{Inflation|US|0.1|1889|r=1|fmt=c}} million today) and relocated to Iowa, intending to be a rural banker.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Richard-W-Sears|title=Richard W. Sears \u2013 American merchant |website=britannica.com}}</ref> Sears returned to Chicago in 1892 and established a new mail-order firm, again selling watches and jewelry, with Roebuck as his partner, operating as the A. C. Roebuck watch company. In 1893, they renamed the company to '''Sears, Roebuck & Company''' and began to diversify the product lines offered in their catalogs. \n\nBefore the Sears catalog, farmers near small rural towns usually purchased supplies, often at high prices and on credit, from local [[general store]]s with narrow selections of goods. Prices were negotiated and relied on the storekeeper's estimate of a customer's creditworthiness. Sears took advantage of this by publishing catalogs offering customers a wider selection of products at clearly stated prices. \n\nBy 1894, the Sears catalog had grown to 322 pages, including many new items such as sewing machines, bicycles, [[sports equipment|sporting goods]], and automobiles (later produced, from 1905 to 1915, by [[Lincoln Motor Car Works]] of Chicago, no relation to the current [[Lincoln (automobile)|Ford line]]).<ref>Clymer, Floyd. ''Treasury of Early American Automobiles, 1877\u20131925''. (New York: Bonanza, 1950), p.90.</ref> By 1895, the company was producing a 532-page catalog. Sales were greater than $400,000 (${{Inflation|US|0.4|1893|r=1|fmt=c}} million today) in 1893 and more than $750,000 (${{Inflation|US|0.75|1895|r=1|fmt=c}} million today) two years later.<ref>[http://www.searsarchives.com/history/history1890s.htm \"Sears History \u2013 1890s.\"] ''Sears''. Last updated September 27, 2004.</ref> By 1896, dolls, stoves, and groceries had been added to the catalog.\n\n[[File: Sears Merchandise Building Tower.jpg|right|thumb|upright|The exterior of the [[Sears Merchandise Building Tower]]]]\nDespite the strong and growing sales, the national [[Panic of 1893]] led to a full-scale [[recession]], causing a cash squeeze and large quantities of unsold merchandise by 1895. Roebuck decided to quit, returning later in a publicity role. Sears offered Roebuck's half of the company to Chicago businessman [[Aaron Nusbaum]], who in turn brought in his brother-in-law [[Julius Rosenwald]], to whom Sears owed money. In August 1895, they bought Roebuck's half of the company for $75,000 (${{Inflation|US|0.075|1895|r=1|fmt=c}} million today). The company was reincorporated in Illinois with a capital stock of $150,000 (${{Inflation|US|0.15|1895|r=1|fmt=c}} million today) in August 1895. The 1895 transaction was handled by [[Albert Henry Loeb]] of Chicago law firm Loeb & Adler (now [[Arnstein & Lehr, LLP]]). Copies of the transaction documents are now displayed on the walls of the law firm.<ref>Arnstein & Lehr, The First 120 Years (2013).</ref>\n\nSears and Rosenwald got along well with each other, but not with Nusbaum; they bought him out for $1.3 million in 1903 (${{Inflation|US|1.3|1903|r=1|fmt=c}} million today).<ref>Emmet and Jack, ''Catalogues and Counters'' (1950) pp 47\u201353</ref> Rosenwald brought to the mail-order firm a rational management philosophy and diversified product lines: dry goods, consumer durables, drugs, hardware, furniture, and nearly anything else a farm household could desire.\n\nIn September 1904, a freight elevator carrying 10 people fell three stories at a Sears store in Chicago, killing two people and seriously injuring six others. The freight elevator was being used because the passenger elevator was out of service for repairs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Two Killed And Six Injured in Accident In Chicago Store |publisher=[[Indiana Democrat]] |date=7 September 1904 |url=http://www.gendisasters.com/illinois/15491/chicago-il-elevator-accident-sep-1904}}</ref>\n\nSales continued to grow rapidly, and the prosperity of the company and their vision for greater expansion led Sears and Rosenwald to take the company public in 1906, with a stock placement of $40 million (${{Inflation|US|0.04|1906|r=1|fmt=c}} billion today). They had to incorporate a new company in order to bring the operation public; Sears and Rosenwald established '''Sears, Roebuck and Company''' with the legal name '''Sears, Roebuck and Co.''', in the state of New York, which effectively replaced the original company.<ref>https://cepi.io/companies/sears-roebuck-and-co-/us_ny/27644 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042417/https://cepi.io/companies/sears-roebuck-and-co-/us_ny/27644 |date=December 1, 2017}} Sears, Roebuck and Company (Co.) 1906 New York incorporation</ref> The current company inherits the history of the old company, celebrating the original 1892 incorporation, rather than the 1906 revision, as the start of the company.\n\nSears' successful 1906 [[initial public offering]] (IPO) marks the first major retail IPO in American financial history and represented a coming of age, financially, of the consumer sector.<ref>Gregory D. L. Morris, \"Attention Shoppers: 1906 Sears IPO Heralds the Triumph of the Consumer Economy,\" ''Financial History'' (2007), Issue 88, pp 20\u201336</ref> The company traded under the ticker symbol S and was a component of the [[Historical components of the Dow Jones Industrial Average|Dow Jones Industrial Average]] from 1924 to 1999.\n\nIn 1906, Sears opened its catalog plant and the Sears Merchandise Building Tower in [[West Side, Chicago|Chicago's West Side]].<ref>Book: Historic Sears, Roebuck and Co. Catalog Plant {{ISBN|0-7385-3977-5}}, opening date.</ref> The building was the anchor of what would become the massive {{convert|40|acre|ha|adj=on}} [[Sears, Roebuck and Company Complex]] of offices, laboratories and mail-order operations at Homan Avenue and Arthington Street. The complex served as corporate headquarters until 1973 when the [[Sears Tower]] was completed and served as the base of the mail-order catalog business until 1993.\n\nBy 1907, under Rosenwald's leadership as Vice President and Treasurer, annual sales of the company climbed to roughly $50 million (${{Inflation|US|0.050|1907|r=1|fmt=c}} billion today). Sears resigned the presidency in 1908 due to declining health, with Rosenwald named president and chairman of the board and taking on full control.<ref>Emmet and Jack, ''Catalogues and Counters'' (1950) pp 53\u201357</ref>\n\nThe company was badly hurt during [[Post\u2013World War I recession|1919\u201321 as a severe depression]] hit the nation's farms after farmers had over-expanded their holdings. To bail out the company, Rosenwald pledged $21 million (${{Inflation|US|0.021|1921|r=1|fmt=c}} billion today) of his personal wealth in 1921.<ref>{{cite news |title=Julius Rosenwald Pledges $20,000,000 For Sears-Roebuck |work=[[New York Times]] |date=December 30, 1921 |id={{ProQuest|98483996}} }}</ref>\n\nBy 1922, Sears had regained financial stability. Rosenwald oversaw the design and construction of the firm's first department store, built on land within the Sears, Roebuck and Company Complex. The store opened in 1925. In 1924, Rosenwald resigned the presidency, but remained as chairman until his death in 1932; his goal was to devote more time to philanthropy.<ref>Peter M. Ascoli, ''Julius Rosenwald: The Man Who Built Sears, Roebuck And Advanced the Cause of Black Education in the American South'', (2006).</ref>\n\nIn 1933 Sears issued the first of its Christmas catalogs known as the \"[[Sears Wishbook]]\", a catalog featuring toys and gifts, separate from the annual Christmas Catalog. From 1908 to 1940, it included ready-to-assemble [[Sears Catalog Home]] kit houses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.modulartoday.com/searshomes.html |title=Sears mail-order homes |accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Sears catalog became known in the industry as \"the Consumers' Bible\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robertpassikoff/2014/01/22/a-love-song-to-mr-sears-mr-roebuck-they-could-use-one-about-now/#200ace931f68|title=A Love Song To Mr. Sears &amp; Mr. Roebuck, Who Could Use One About Now|last=Passikoff|first=Robert|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-11-28|language=en}}</ref> The company sold to foreign customers, such as after the American occupation of [[Greenland in World War II]] when locals ordered from catalogs left by soldiers.<ref name=\"lockhart20191227\">{{Cite magazine |last=Lockhart |first=Katie |date=2019-12-27 |title=How This Abandoned Mining Town in Greenland Helped Win World War II |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/travel/how-abandoned-mining-town-greenland-helped-win-world-war-ii-180973835/ |magazine=Smithsonian |language=en |access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> Novelists and story writers often portrayed the importance of the catalog in the emotional lives of rural folk. The catalog also entered the language, particularly of rural dwellers, as a [[euphemism]] for toilet paper, as its pages could be torn out and used as such.<ref>{{cite news |title=Why toilet paper belongs to America |author=Rodriguez, Linda |work=CNN.com |date=July 8, 2009 |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/LIVING/wayoflife/07/07/mf.toilet.paper.history/index.html |accessdate=August 29, 2010}}</ref> In addition, for many rural African-Americans, especially in areas dominated by [[Jim Crow]] [[racial segregation]], the Sears Catalogue was a vital retail alternative to local white-population-dominated stores, bypassing the stores' frequent intention to deny them fair access to their merchandise.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Farzan |first1=Antonia Noori |title=How Sears mail-order catalogs undermined Jim Crow racism |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-biz-sears-history-racism-jim-crow-20181016-story.html |accessdate=19 October 2018 |agency=Washington Post |newspaper=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\n===Retail stores and diversification===\n[[File:KM 5939 sears tower august 2007 B.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The Sears Tower, now the Willis Tower]]\n\nThe mail-order market was based on rural America, with a slow-growing population and far less spending power than urban America. Rosenwald decided to shift emphasis to urban America and brought in [[Robert E. Wood]] to take charge. The first Sears retail stores were opened in conjunction with the company's mail-order offices, typically in working-class neighborhoods far from the main shopping center. Sears was a pioneer in creating department stores that catered to men as well as women, especially with lines of hardware and building materials. It deemphasized the latest fashions in favor of practicality and durability and allowed customers to select goods without the aid of a clerk. Its stores were oriented to motorists\u2014set apart from existing business districts amid residential areas occupied by their target audience; had ample, free, off-street parking; and communicated a clear corporate identity. In the 1930s, the company designed fully air-conditioned, \"windowless\" stores whose layout was driven wholly by merchandising concerns.<ref>Richard Longstreth, \"Sears, Roebuck and the Remaking of the Department Store, 1924\u201342,\" ''Journal of the Society of Architectural Historians'' (2006) 65#2 pp 238\u2013279</ref>\n\nFrom the 1920s to the 1950s, Sears built many urban department stores in the US, Canada and Mexico (apart from, but not far from, existing [[central business district]]s), and they overshadowed the mail-order business. Starting in the 1950s, the company expanded into suburban markets and malls in the 1960s and 1970s. In 1959, it had formed the [[Homart Development Company]] for developing malls. Many of the company's stores have undergone major renovations or replacement since the 1980s. Sears began to diversify in the 1930s, creating [[Allstate|Allstate Insurance Company]] in 1931 and placing Allstate representatives in its stores in 1934. Over the decades it established major national brands, such as [[Kenmore Appliances|Kenmore]], [[Craftsman (tools)|Craftsman]], [[Diehard (type of battery)|DieHard]], [[Silvertone (instruments)|Silvertone]], [[Supertone Records|Supertone]], and [[Toughskins]]. The company became a [[conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] during the mid-20th century, adding [[Dean Witter]] and [[Coldwell Banker]] real estate in 1981, starting [[Prodigy (online service)|Prodigy]] as a joint venture with [[IBM]] in 1984, and introducing the [[Discover Card|Discover credit card]] in 1985.\n\nIn 1974, Sears completed the 110-story [[Willis Tower|Sears Tower]] in Chicago, which became the [[List of tallest buildings and structures in the world#Tallest buildings|world's tallest building]], a title it took from the former [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] towers in New York. Sears moved to the new Prairie Stone Business Park in Hoffman Estates, Illinois, between 1993 and 1995.<ref>[http://www.prairiestone.com/transport_publictransport.html] Prairie Stone Transportation site.</ref> The [[Sears Centre]] is a 10,001-seat multi-purpose arena located in Hoffman Estates adjacent to the Prairie Stone campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoffmanestates.com/government/SearsCentre.shtml |title=Sears Centre Arena |publisher=[[Hoffman Estates, Illinois|The Village of Hoffman Estates]] |accessdate=February 7, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070212074252/http://www.hoffmanestates.com/government/SearsCentre.shtml |archivedate=February 12, 2007 |df=mdy-all}} Prairie Stone Business Park, Current Sears headquarters location and Sears Centre.</ref>\n\nSears reached its pinnacle in 1972\u20134, after which it was challenged by other retailers such as [[Home Depot]], [[Best Buy]], and [[Walmart]]\u2014challenges Sears was ultimately unable to meet.<ref name=wsj>{{cite news |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/money/companies/how-sears-lost-the-american-shopper/ar-BBUO2bk?li=BBnb7Kz |title=How Sears lost the American shopper |author1= Suzanne Kapner |date=March 15, 2019 |newspaper=Wall Street Journal | accessdate=March 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Sears Roebuck purchased [[Western Auto]] from Wesray Capital.<ref name=\"suntimes88\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1988-03-17/business/8803010487_1_sears-annual-sales-western-auto-sears-automotive-centers |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |title=Sears Buying Western Auto Supply |last=Key |first=Janet |date=March 17, 1988 |accessdate=April 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Decline and Kmart merger===\n{{Main|Sears Holdings Corporation}}\nIn the 1990s a series of pricing scandals were revealed. California successfully sued the company in 1992 for falsely finding things wrong with automobiles in for repair for other reasons.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-09-03/business/fi-7430_1_auto-repair-fraud |title=Sears to Repair Image With $46 Million in Coupons : Retailing: It may be the largest such consumer fraud settlement ever. California auto centers will be on probation for 3 years. |author1=DENISE GELLENE |date=September 3, 1992 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times | accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref> In 1997, criminal charges were made.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.newsweek.com/sorry-side-sears-168892 |title=The Sorry Side Of Sears |author1= John McCormick |date=February 2, 1999 |magazine=Newsweek | accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tirebusiness.com/article/19950821/ISSUE/308219991/sears-slapped-with-tire-service-fraud-suit|title=SEARS SLAPPED WITH TIRE SERVICE FRAUD SUIT|first=Sigmund J.|last=Mikolajczyk|website=Tire Business|accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThere was a lot of diversification that was needed, but it distracted management's attention from the competition. Management, at first, discounted the threat from Walmart and Best Buy because of lower quality and lack of dedicated salespersons for appliances.<ref name=wsj/> However, appliances turned over slowly and contributed weakly to net profit.<ref name=wsj/> As it turned out, Walmart reset prices for the country.<ref name=wsj/>\n\nEven though its naming rights to the building expired in 2003, the Sears Tower remained named as such until early 2009. In March 2009 London-based insurer [[Willis Group Holdings|Willis Group Holdings, Ltd.]], was given the building's naming rights to encourage them to occupy the building. The official renaming as the ''Willis Tower'' took place on Thursday, July 16, 2009, during a public ceremony hosted by Willis Group Holdings.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/topNews/idUSTRE52B54J20090312 |title=Tallest U.S. building to get new name |work=Reuters |date=March 12, 2009 |accessdate=July 17, 2009 |first=Michael |last=Conlon}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, the company began divesting itself of many non-retail entities, which were detrimental to the company's bottom line. Sears spun off its financial services arm which included brokerage business Dean Witter Reynolds and Discover Card. It sold its mall building subsidiary Homart to [[General Growth Properties]] in 1995.<ref name=\"npr1\">{{cite news |url= https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=103172409 |title= Retail Real Estate Braces For Sell-Off |author= Jim Zarroli |publisher=[[National Public Radio]] |date= April 19, 2009}}</ref> Sears later acquired hardware chain [[Orchard Supply Hardware]] in 1996 and started home improvement store The Great Indoors in 1997.<ref>Donald R. Katz, ''The Big Store'' (1987)</ref>\n\nThe cost of distributing the once highly influential general merchandise catalog became prohibitive; sales and profits had declined. The company discontinued the catalog in 1993. It dismissed 50,000 workers who had filled the orders. This was before the internet became an effective tool. With the advantage of hindsight, the timing was poor; Sears already had in place what it took [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] years to achieve.<ref name=wsj/>\n\nSears eventually held sales on all items. The dedicated customer would just wait until the item was on sale to buy. In the meantime, the item took up valuable floor space. This was a marketing policy misjudgment.<ref name=wsj/>\n\nAfter weeks of speculation in 1998, Sears announced it had sold the remnants of Western Auto to [[Roanoke, Virginia|Roanoke]]-based [[Advance Auto Parts]]. The business deal was not quite what experts in the after-market automotive industry expected. Specifically, in return, Sears Roebuck became \"one of the largest shareholders\" after obtaining a 40% stake in Advance Auto Parts, and by merging their two store networks, which included Western Auto's wholesale and retail operations. More precisely, the existing store network of Advance Auto Parts, comprising 915 stores in 17 U.S. states, merged with 590 U.S.-based Parts America Stores in addition to 40 Western Auto stores in the [[Puerto Rico|Commonwealth of Puerto Rico]].\n\nIn 1997 Sears sold 85% of [[Sears (Mexico)|its Mexico affiliate]] to [[Grupo Carso]]. Sears Holdings continues to produce specialty catalogs and reintroduced a smaller version of the Holiday Wish Book in 2007. In 2003, Sears sold its U.S. retail credit card operation to [[Citibank]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Sorkin |first=Andrew Ross |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/07/16/business/sears-to-sell-card-portfolio-to-citigroup-for-3-billion.html |title=Sears to Sell Card Portfolio To Citigroup For $3 Billion |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 16, 2003 |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref> The remaining card operations for Sears Canada were sold to [[JPMorgan Chase]] in August 2005.<ref name=\"ct-2005sep01\">{{cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2005-09-01-0509010046-story.html |title=JPMorgan to buy credit card unit of Sears Canada |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=September 1, 2005 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref> In 2003, Sears opened a new concept store called Sears Grand. Sears Grand stores carry everything that a regular Sears carries, and more. Sears Grand stores are about {{convert|175000|to|225000|sqft|m2}}.\n\nOn November 17, 2004, Kmart Holdings Corporation announced it was going to acquire Sears Roebuck & Co. for $11 billion after Kmart completed its bankruptcy (USA Today Nov. 17, 2004). As a part of the acquisition, Kmart Holding Corporation along with Sears Roebuck & Co. was transformed into the new [[Sears Holdings Corporation]]. The new company started trading on the NASDAQ stock exchange as SHLD; Sears sold its single-letter ticker symbol 'S' in the [[New York Stock Exchange]] it had held since 1910 to [[Sprint Corporation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-02-02/business/0502020283_1_sears-and-kmart-ticker-symbol-sears-holdings-corp |title=S stands for Sears, but not much longer |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=February 2, 2005 |accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref>{{better citation needed|reason=The currently linked story does not reference a *sale* of the symbol. Sears relinquishes the symbol because it's leaving the NYSE|date=April 2019}} The new corporation announced that it would continue to operate stores under both the Sears and Kmart brands. In 2005, the company began renovating some Kmart stores and converting them to the Sears Essentials format, only to change them later to Sears Grands.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/news.pl?id=19617 |title=Sears ditches Sears Essentials name |publisher=Chicagobusiness.com |date=February 22, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe combined company's profits peaked at $1.5 billion in 2006. By 2010, the company was no longer profitable; from 2011 to 2016 the company lost $10.4 billion. In 2014, its total debt ($4.2 billion at the end of January 2017) exceeded its market capitalization ($974.1 million as of March 21, 2017).<ref>{{cite web|title=Who Killed Sears? 50 Years on the Road to Ruin|work=Investopedia|url=http://www.investopedia.com/news/downfall-of-sears|date=3 November 2017|accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nSears spent much of 2014 and 2015 selling off portions of its balance sheet; namely, Lands' End and its stake in [[Sears Canada]], one of the biggest e-commerce players in Canada, with [[C$]]505 million in sales in 2015\u2014more than Walmart and others who had begun pushing aggressively into online sales, such as [[Canadian Tire]].<ref name=\"Sears Holdings\">{{cite web |url=http://fortune.com/fortune500/sears-holdings-99/ |title=Sears Holdings |accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref> Sears stated that the company was looking to focus on becoming a more tech-driven retailer. Sears' CEO and top shareholder said the sell-off of key assets in the last year had given the retailer the money it needs to speed up its transformation.<ref name=\" Sears Holdings\"/> Sears Holdings had lost a total of US$7 billion in the four years to 2015. In part, the retailer was trying to curb losses by using a loyalty program called Shop Your Way.<ref name=\"Sears Holdings\"/> Sears believed the membership scheme would enhance repeat business and customer loyalty in the long term.<ref name=\" Sears Holdings\"/>\n\nSeritage Growth Properties is a [[real estate investment trust]] that was created and spun-off by Sears Holdings to act as owner of the spun-off 235 Sears and Kmart properties that were transferred to Seritage.<ref name=\"forbes-2015dec10\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/gurufocus/2015/12/10/buffett-buys-8-stake-in-sears-spin-off-seritage-growth-properties/ |title=Buffett Buys 8% Stake In Sears Spin-Off Seritage Growth Properties |magazine=[[Forbes]] |date=December 10, 2015 |first=Holly |last=LaFon}}</ref> In September 2016, Sears Holdings terminated 17 Kmart store leases and paid Seritage a termination fee.<ref name=terminate>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/01/04/sears-closing-more-stores-as-game-of-financial-jenga-continues.html | title=Sears closing more stores as game of financial Jenga continues | first=Krystina | last=Gustafson | work=[[CNBC]] | date=January 4, 2017}}</ref> Lampert is also chairman and largest shareholder in Seritage.<ref name=\"nyt-2018aug28\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/28/business/sears-seritage-edward-lampert.html?pagewanted=all |title=As Sears Withers, Its Former Stores Fuel a New Fortune |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=August 28, 2018 |first=Michael |last=Corkery}}</ref> Seritage Growth Properties is controlled by ESL Investments.\n\nIn October 2016, Moody's Investor Services downgraded Sears to speculative grade liquidity rating, and predicted that Sears was expected to have to rely on external financing and monetization of its alternative assets, according to Moody's VP Christina Boni.<ref name=terminate/>\n\nIn late 2016 and early 2017, some significant steps were taken by [[Edward Lampert]], president, chief executive officer and top shareholder of Sears Holding Corp. Lampert, with personal assets estimated at US$2 [[billion]], is also the founder and manager of the hedge fund ESL Investments Inc.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/edward-lampert/ |title=#309 Edward Lampert |date=January 22, 2017 |website=Forbes |access-date=January 22, 2017 |quote=...took over as Sears CEO in 2013 ... has presided over a remarkable dismantling.}}</ref> He provided an additional loan of US$500 million to the company and said he would provide letters of credit to Sears for additional amounts, reportedly totaling US$200 million and possibly increasing to a half-billion dollars in the future.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20170105/NEWS07/170109930/with-craftsman-sale-sears-takes-another-step-toward-the-grave |title=With Craftsman sale, Sears takes another step toward the grave |last=Sweeney |first=Brigid |date=January 5, 2017 |website=Chicago Business |publisher=Crain Communication, Inc. |access-date=January 9, 2017 |quote=The company may need $2.5 billion in cash to get through 2017 amid sales declines and store closures, including almost $600 million in minimum pension contributions.}}</ref>\n\nLampert also concluded an arrangement that sold the Craftsman brand to [[Stanley Black & Decker|Stanley Black & Decker Inc.]] for approximately US$900 million.<ref>{{cite news |date=January 9, 2016 |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2017/01/09/lamperts-rescue-of-sears-puts-him-on-the-hook-for-12-billion.html?source=newsletter |title=Lampert's rescue of Sears puts him on the hook for $1.2 billion |author=Lauren Coleman-Lochner and Brendan Coffey, Bloomberg |newspaper=Toronto Star |location=Toronto, Canada |access-date=January 9, 2016}}</ref> During this period, the company also announced that it would close 150 stores (109 Kmart and 41 Sears outlets), in an attempt to cut its losses after a decline in sales of 12 to 13 percent during the holiday shopping season and the largest quarterly loss since 2013. Matt McGinley, an analyst at Evercore ISI, stated, \"In the long run, the cash isn't likely to change the company's course. ... I don't think there is any viable path to any sort of profitability.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-01-05/stanley-to-buy-craftsman-brand-from-sears-for-about-900-million |title=Sears to Sell Craftsman, Shut 150 Stores as Lampert Raises Cash |last=Coleman-Lochner |first=Lauren |date=January 5, 2017 |website=Bloomberg |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |access-date=January 9, 2017 |quote=Investors cheered the moves, sending Sears up as much as 8 percent to $11.19 in New York. The stock had slumped 55 percent last year as the company continued to post losses.}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Sears announced a restructuring plan that it hoped would cut costs by US$1 billion, via selling more stores, cutting jobs and selling brands.<ref>[http://jacksonville.com/business/2017-03-22/sears-has-substantial-doubt-about-its-future Sears has 'substantial doubt' about its future] Associated Press, Retrieved March 22, 2017</ref> During the second quarter of 2017, 42 Sears stores in 40 states closed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2017/01/05/sears-kmart-stores-closing/96195504/|title=Is your local Sears or Kmart among 150 stores to be axed? See the list|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=January 5, 2017|accessdate=March 22, 2017}}</ref> Sears later announced that it closed an additional 12 stores.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jones|first1=Charisse|title=Sears quietly closing 30 more stores|url=https://a.msn.com/r/2/BBBjN3h?m=en-us|accessdate=20 May 2017|work=USA Today|date=19 May 2017}}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> In May 2017, Sears announced it would close 20 stores, including the last Sears store in [[Rhode Island]], at [[Rhode Island Mall]] in [[Warwick, Rhode Island|Warwick]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2017/06/23/sears-holdings-store-closure-lista/424590001/|title=20 more Sears stores closing: see the list|website=USA TODAY|accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref> In July 2017, Sears announced it would close another 43 stores (8 Sears and 35 Kmart stores).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Naidu|first1=Richa|title=Sears to close 43 more stores to cut costs|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/sears-restructuring-idINL1N1JY1QZ|accessdate=9 July 2017|work=Reuters|date=7 Jul 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Further decline and bankruptcy===\n[[File:ClosedSears2019.jpg|thumb|right|A closed Sears store at [[Stones River Town Centre]], in [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]] in April 2019, with signage still intact. The store closed earlier that year on February 11th.]]\nSears declined from more than 3,500 physical stores to 695 US stores from 2010 to 2017.<ref name=\"number stores q4 2016\">{{cite web|url=https://searsholdings.com/docs/investor/eap/q4-2016-shc-earnings-release.pdf |title=Sears Holdings Fourth Quarter 2016 Earnings Release|publisher= Sears Holdings |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref> Sales at Sears stores dropped 10.3&nbsp;percent in the final quarter of 2016 when compared to the same period in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-sears-lampert-stock-buy-0328-biz-20170327-story.html|title=Sears CEO Lampert takes bigger stake in ailing chain, shares jump|last=Zumbach|first=Lauren|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=March 27, 2017|accessdate=March 28, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Sears and appliance manufacturer [[Whirlpool Corporation]] ended their 101-year old association, reportedly due to pricing issues, although Whirlpool continued supplying Sears with [[Kenmore (brand)|Kenmore]]-branded appliances.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stych|first1=Ed|title=Sears splits with Whirlpool appliances, splintering 101-year relationship|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/dayton/news/2017/10/25/sears-splits-with-whirlpool-appliances-splintering.html|accessdate=5 January 2018|work=Dayton Business Journal|date=October 25, 2017}}</ref> Another wave of 63 store closures, including 18 Sears, was announced in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/11/03/sears-is-closing-63-more-stores.html|title=Sears is closing 63 more stores|first=Lauren|last=Thomas|date=November 3, 2017|website=www.cnbc.com|accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref> The retailer declined to run television advertisements for the 2017 holiday season, citing a desire to focus on online advertising.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fortune.com/2017/12/31/sears-kmart-no-tv-advertising-holiday-shopping-season/ |title=Sears and Kmart Didn't Run TV Ads During the Peak Holiday Shopping Season |magazine=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |date=December 31, 2017 |first=David Z. |last=Morris}}</ref>\nThe retailer announced several waves of store closures throughout 2018:\n*103 stores, including 39 Sears, in January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/04/sears-is-closing-more-than-100-more-stores.html|title=Sears is closing over 100 more stores|first=Lauren|last=Thomas|date=January 4, 2018|website=www.cnbc.com|accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n*63 stores, including 48 Sears, in May, including the last Sears store in [[Montana]], in [[Billings, Montana|Billings]], the last Sears store in [[North Dakota]], in [[Grand Forks, North Dakota|Grand Forks]], and the last Sears store in [[South Dakota]], in [[Sioux Falls, South Dakota|Sioux Falls]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/05/31/news/companies/sears-store-closings-sales-losses/index.html|title=Sears is closing 63 more stores|first=Chris|last=Isidore|date=May 31, 2018|website=CNNMoney|accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n*15 stores, including 6 Sears, in July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/nation-now/2018/07/02/sears-closings-78-kmart-and-sears-closing-september/750127002/|title=Sears adds more stores to closings list; 78 set to close in September|website=USA TODAY|accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n*46 stores, including 33 Sears, in August, with the last Utah store, in West Jordan, which was downsized from the first and largest Sears Grand in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/23/sears-is-closing-46-more-stores-heres-where-they-are.html|title=Sears is closing 46 more stores \u2014 here's where they are|first=Lauren|last=Thomas|date=August 23, 2018|website=www.cnbc.com|accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n*142 stores, including 79 Sears in October, with the last Wyoming store, in Casper.\n*40 stores, including 29 Sears in November, with the last Idaho store, in Idaho Falls, and the last Mississippi stores, in Meridian and Tupelo.\n*80 stores, including 43 Sears, in December, all set to close by March 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thomas |first1=Lauren |title=Sears closing 80 more stores in March as it faces possible liquidation |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/12/28/sears-closing-80-more-stores-in-march-faces-possible-liquidation.html |website=www.cnbc.com |accessdate=29 December 2018 |date=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe company also auctioned some real estate, including the buildings of several operating stores, online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/11/sears-to-auction-off-16-stores-online.html|title=16 Sears stores are being auctioned online|first=Lauren|last=Thomas|date=April 11, 2018|website=cnbc.com}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Sears announced it had formed a \"special committee\" to explore the sale of Kenmore.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/05/14/news/companies/sears-kenmore-sale/index.html|title=Sears moves to sell Kenmore|last=Isidore|first=Chris|work=CNNMoney|access-date=2018-08-22}}</ref> In August 2018, Lampert's ESL Investments Inc submitted a bid of US$400 million for the brand. As of October 14, 2018, with Sears filing for chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, leaving the future of both the Kenmore and DieHard brands undecided, it has been rumored online and elsewhere that Whirlpool Corporation could emerge as a possible top potential buyer for the Kenmore brand since they were the top major manufacturer of Kenmore appliances for well over a century.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/sears-pensions/rpt-focus-in-kenmore-sale-sears-pension-liabilities-come-back-to-bite-idUSL2N1VC1GC|title=RPT-FOCUS-In Kenmore sale, Sears' pension liabilities come back to...|last=DiNapoli|first=Jessica|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn September 24, 2018, the retailer's CEO warned that the company was \"running out of time\" to salvage its business.<ref>[https://money.cnn.com/2018/09/24/news/companies/sears-eddie-lampert/index.html Time is running out for Sears, CEO warns] CNN Money, September 24, 2018</ref> Sears Holdings filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy on October 15, 2018, ahead of a $134 million debt payment due that day.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2018/10/15/sears-nears-bankruptcy-after-years-turmoil/ Sears files for bankruptcy after years of turmoil] ''The Washington Post'', October 15, 2018</ref> Liquidation sales at 142 stores, including 79 Sears locations, including the last Sears store in [[Wyoming]], at [[Eastridge Mall (Casper)|Eastridge Mall]] in [[Casper, Wyoming|Casper]], began later in the month,<ref>[https://searsholdings.com/docs/101518_store_closing_list.pdf List of closing stores] Sears Holdings</ref> with 46 stores to be closed by November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/business/201810151068899979-sears-bankruptcy-debt-retail/|title=US Retail Giant Sears Files for Bankruptcy, Blames E-Commerce for Failings|last=Sputnik|website=sputniknews.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref> On November 8, 2018, Sears Holdings announced it would close an additional 40 stores, including 29 Sears stores, including the last Sears store in [[Idaho]], at [[Grand Teton Mall]] in [[Idaho Falls, Idaho|Idaho Falls]], and the last two Sears stores in [[Mississippi]], at [[Bonita Lakes Mall]] in [[Meridian, Mississippi|Meridian]], and at the [[Mall at Barnes Crossing]] in [[Tupelo, Mississippi|Tupelo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/08/sears-to-shut-40-more-stores-early-next-year.html|title=Sears to shut 40 more stores early next year|last=Hirsch|first=Lauren Thomas, Lauren|date=2018-11-08|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> On November 23, 2018, Sears Holdings released a list of 505 stores, including 266 Sears stores, that are for sale in the bankruptcy process while all others are currently holding liquidation sales.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://seekingalpha.com/article/4224133-list-sears-stores-sold-bankruptcy-developments|title=List Of Sears Stores To Be Sold And Other Bankruptcy Developments|last=Researcher|first=WYCO|date=2018-11-23|work=Seeking Alpha|access-date=2018-11-24|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn January 16, 2019, Sears Holdings announced it would remain open after Lampert won a bankruptcy auction for the company with an offer to keep about 400 stores open.<ref name=\":0\" /> On February 7, 2019, a bankruptcy judge approved a $5.2 billion plan by Sears\u2019 chairman and biggest shareholder to keep the iconic business going. The approval means roughly 425 stores and 45,000 jobs will be preserved.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-sears-bankruptcy-20190207-story.html|title=Sears gets to stay in business: Bankruptcy judge OKs Eddie Lampert's plan |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=February 2018 |accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Sears announced it was opening three new stores with a limited set of merchandise under the name Sears Home & Life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.retaildive.com/news/sears-opening-stores-for-a-change/552036/|title=Sears opening stores for a change|website=Retail Dive|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-04}}</ref> Also that month, Sears closed its store at [[Windward Mall]] in [[Kaneohe, Hawaii]], and its store at [[Oakbrook Center]] in [[Oak Brook, Illinois]], making it the first post-bankruptcy closure for the brand since being bought by ESL.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/04/15/breaking-news/windward-mall-sears-closing-on-april-28/|title=Windward Mall Sears closing on April 28|first1=By Kristen Consillio|last1=kconsillio@staradvertiser.com|first2=2019|last2=April 15|date=April 15, 2019|website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/oak-brook/ct-dob-sears-closing-tl-0425-story.html|title=Sears closing Oakbrook Center store Sunday; liquidation under way|first=Chuck|last=Fieldman|website=chicagotribune.com}}</ref>\n\nOn June 3, 2019, it was announced that Transform Holdco LLC would acquire [[Sears Hometown and Outlet Stores]]. As per deal, they might need to divest its Sears Outlet division to gain approval.<ref name=\"WBBM\"/> On August 6, 2019, it was announced that 26 stores, including 21 Sears stores, including the last Sears store in [[Alabama]], at [[Riverchase Galleria]] in [[Hoover, Alabama|Hoover]], and the last Sears store in [[West Virginia]], at [[Huntington Mall]] in [[Barboursville, West Virginia|Barboursville]], would be closing in October with plans to \"accelerate the expansion of our smaller store formats which includes opening additional Home & Life stores and adding several hundred Sears Hometown stores after the Sears Hometown and Outlet transaction closes.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tyko |first1=Kelly |title=Sears and Kmart store closings: 26 stores to close in October |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/08/06/sears-and-kmart-store-closings-2019-26-stores-close-october/1940039001/ |accessdate=August 7, 2019 |work=USA Today |date=August 6, 2019}}</ref> On August 31, 2019, it was announced that Transform would close an additional 92 stores, including 15 Sears stores, by the end of 2019. 100 more stores are expected to close by January 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tyko |first1=Kelly |title=Kmart, Sears store closings: More locations to shutter by end of 2019 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/08/31/kmart-sears-store-closings-more-locations-shutter-end-2019/2168435001/ |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |work=USA Today |date=August 31, 2019}}</ref> 51 Sears stores are scheduled to close in February 2020, including the last full-line store in [[Las Vegas]], at [[Meadows Mall]].<ref>\"[https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/11/07/kmart-sears-store-closings-96-stores-set-shutter-february-2020/2521653001/ Sears and Kmart store closings: 51 Sears, 45 Kmart locations to shutter. See the list]\", ''[[USA Today]]''. November 7, 2019. Retrieved November 8, 2019.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox5vegas.com/news/sears-to-close-last-mall-anchored-store-in-las-vegas/article_e6b66e84-04a2-11ea-bc63-6f45c6392806.html|title=Sears to close last mall-anchored store in Las Vegas|last=Lilly|first=Caitlin|website=FOX5 Las Vegas|language=en|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> On January 23, 2020, it was announced that the Sears in Glendale, California, is scheduled to close on March 15, 2020.<ref>\"[https://www.latimes.com/socal/glendale-news-press/news/story/2020-01-23/sears-glendale-closing-after-85-years Sears in Glendale to shutter after 85 years]\", ''[[Glendale News-Press]]''. January 23, 2020. Retrieved January 23, 2020.</ref>\n\nOn February 5, 2020, it was announced that the Sears stores in [[Livingston, New Jersey|Livingston]] and [[New Brunswick, New Jersey|New Brunswick]] in [[New Jersey]] are scheduled to close in mid-April. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nj.com.com/business/2020/02/sears-will-close-stores-in-livingston-and-new-brunswick.html|title=Sears will close stores in Livingston and New Brunswick|first=Nicolette|last=Accardi|date=February 6, 2020|website=nj}}</ref> On February 6, 2020, it was announced that seven more Sears stores would be closing in mid-April, including the last Sears store in [[Delaware]], at the [[Concord Mall (Delaware)|Concord Mall]] in [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmtw.com/article/one-of-maines-last-two-sears-department-stores-to-close/30793539|title=One of Maine's last two Sears department stores to close|date=February 6, 2020|website=WMTW}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://delawarebusinesstimes.com/news/sears-close-concord-mall/|title=Sears to close Concord Mall store; last in Delaware|date=February 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>https://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/news/2020/02/06/sears-to-close-three-more-stores-in-maryland.amp.html</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ky3.com/content/news/Sears-posts-closings-signs-on-the-Battlefield-Mall-store-567625411.html|title=Sears announces it will close the Springfield store in the Battlefield Mall|website=www.ky3.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kgun9.com/news/local-news/sears-to-close-tucson-mall-location|title=Sears to close Tucson Mall location|date=February 6, 2020|website=KGUN}}</ref>\n\n==Subsidiaries==\n\n===Current===\n[[File: Sears, Waterford, CT.jpg|thumb|A typical full Sears in the [[Crystal Mall (Connecticut)|Crystal Mall]] in [[Waterford, Connecticut]] in October 2017. This store closed at the end of 2018 as part of a plan to close 142 Kmart and Sears locations.]]\n*'''Sears (Full-Line)''' is a chain of department stores that are usually located in [[shopping mall]]s, however, some freestanding stores exist; they carry clothing, accessories, jewelry, [[home appliance]]s, [[household hardware]], lawn and garden supplies, lawnmowers, paint, sporting goods, automobile repair, and [[electronics]], as well as a portrait studio (in some locations), optical center, and dental center. Sears stores are usually multi-level, averaging {{convert|139000|sqft|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/companyProfile?symbol=SHLD.O |title= Profile: Sears Holdings Corp |accessdate=2017-06-02}}</ref> As of November 3, 2018, there were 409 full-size Sears stores<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1310067/000131006718000029/shldq32018.htm|title=Document|website=www.sec.gov}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://searsholdings.com/press-releases/pr/2110|title=Sears Holdings Reports Second Quarter 2018 Results \u2013 Sears Holdings Corporation|website=searsholdings.com|accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1310067/000131006718000014/shldq12018.htm|title=Document|website=www.sec.gov|accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"number stores q3 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://getfilings.com/sec-filings/170824/SEARS-HOLDINGS-CORP_10-Q/ |title=Form 10-Q for the quarter ending July 29, 2017 \u2013 Sears Holdings Corporation|publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]|accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref> in the United States. There are also 94 in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsarchives.com/history/history1980s.htm|title=Sears History |publisher=Searsmedia.com |date= |accessdate=January 1, 2010}}</ref>{{Failed verification|reason=Number of Mexico locations isn't covered|date=May 2017}}\n*'''Sears Grand''' stores are typically located away from shopping malls (with the exception of [[Gurnee Mills]], [[Gurnee]], [[Illinois]], which closed in September 2018, and formerly [[Pittsburgh Mills]], [[Tarentum, Pennsylvania]], which closed in January 2015). Many Sears Grand locations were retrofit remodels of existing Kmart stores after the merger. They carry everything a Sears department store carries, plus health and beauty products, a pharmacy (in former Kmart locations), toys, baby care, cleaning supplies, home d\u00e9cor, pet food, cards and party supplies, books, magazines, music, movies, and a selection of groceries which is limited mostly to [[dry goods]]. Sears Grand stores range from {{convert|165000|to|210000|sqft|m2}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsmedia.com/aboutsears/businesses/searsgrandfacts.htm |title=Sears Grand Fact Sheet |publisher=Searsmedia.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127060406/http://www.searsmedia.com/sears/businesses/sears_grand.htm|archivedate= January 27, 2016 |accessdate= January 4, 2018}}</ref> The first Sears Grand opened at [[Jordan Landing]] in [[West Jordan, Utah]] in 2003. At {{convert|225000|sqft|m2|-2}}, the Jordan Landing store was the largest in the chain until it was remodeled, downsized, and converted to a regular Sears in 2017 and closed in November 2018. Some other Sears Grands have downsized and converted to regular Sears or Kmart locations.\n*'''Sears Portrait Studio''' is a full-service portrait studio with locations in Sears stores and formerly standalone locations as well. It was run by CPI Corporation until all Sears Portrait Studios ceased operations on April 6, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shropshire|first=Corilyn|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-04-10/business/ct-biz-0410-sears-portrait-2-20130410_1_cpi-corp-sears-holdings-corp-state-street|title=In a flash, portrait studio company closes 2,000-plus U.S. outlets|date=April 10, 2013|accessdate=May 5, 2018}}</ref> CPI Corporation, in a statement on its website, said it closed all of its U.S. studios \"after many years of providing family portrait photography.\" The St. Louis-based company didn't explain the hasty closure, and calls to CPI went unanswered. However, the company has struggled financially, hurt by the rise of digital photography. Sears Portrait Studio was later revived in August 2016 in a few in-store locations through an affiliation with Picture People.\n*'''Sears PartsDirect''' is a chain of lawn & garden equipment and appliance parts stores. Some locations, branded as '''Sears Parts and Repair Centers''', feature a carry-in point for customers to bring-in merchandise which needs to be repaired, either in or out of warranty.\n*'''Sears Travel''' is a licensed business partner of Sears Holdings, founded in February 2012 in conjunction with International Cruise & Excursions, Inc. Sears Vacations functions as an online travel agency that provides online and telephone-based booking services for Sears customers through the SearsVacations.com website. Sears Vacations offers cruises, resorts, hotels, tours, guided vacations, car rental, airline tickets, shore excursions, vacation rentals, and travel insurance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://searsvacations.com |title=Sears Vacations Homepage |publisher=searsvacations.com |date= |accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref>\n*'''Sears Home & Life''' are stores that sell \"hardline\" goods such as appliances, tools, mattresses and lawn and garden equipment. These stores are free-standing and are around {{convert|10,000 to 15,000|sqft}} in size.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/04/04/sears-openings-three-new-home-life-stores-coming-may/3368704002/ |title=The start of a new Sears era? The retailer announces openings, not closings |publisher=usatoday.com |date= |accessdate=April 25, 2019}}</ref> On April 4, 2019, Sears announced that it planned to open three locations. These stores, located in Anchorage, AK, Lafayette, LA, and Overland Park, KS, opened May 24, 2019.\n*'''A&E Factory Service''' is the on-site repair service, servicing larger items such as home appliances, electronics, and garden equipment. The A&E brand name was purchased from [[Montgomery Ward]], which used it for their home service unit, and is a joint venture held by Whirlpool and Sears Holdings.<ref>This Week in Consumer Electronics, Whirlpool Bears First Fruits Of Maytag Merger At Home Depot, September 10, 2006.</ref> A&E Factory Service is a network of mobile service vans with a long history of performing appliance repairs.<ref>Yard and Garden, Filling the gap: now that home centers are \"servicing what they sell,\" where do dealers fit into this rapidly changing retail channel?; Profitably running your service department, March 2005.</ref>\n*'''Sears Home Services''' specializes in onsite Repair, Improvement, and Maintenance of appliances, HVAC systems, Electronics, Fitness equipment, Lawn & Garden, Electrical, Plumbing, Hot water heater both tanked and tankless, whole home water filtration, Insulation install and removal, Crawl space and basement services. other services include Bathroom remodels, Cabinets, Countertops, Flooring, Kitchen remodels, Indoor Sauna Assembly, Roofing, Siding, and Window Replacement. Sears Home Services also offers repair of small appliances in-store.\n**'''Sears Carpet and Upholstery cleaning''' provides Carpet, Upholstery, Hardwood Floor Cleaning, Tile & Grout cleaning services, assist with water damage from emergencies.\n**'''Sears Air Duct Cleaning services''' Air Duct Cleaning, home air filtration systems, and dryer vent cleaning.\n**'''Sears Handyman Solutions'''  Plumbing, Electrical, Installation & Assembly, Home Repair & Maintenance, Drywall, Decks, Fencing, and Painting\n**'''Sears Maid Services''' Home & Apartment Cleaning covers kitchens, bathrooms, bedrooms, and living rooms. Housekeeping services include sweeping, mopping, dusting and surface cleaning in rooms throughout the home. Commercial Cleaning includes common office spaces, as well as building services. Post Construction Cleaning restores living areas after a remodel or repair project, including washing surfaces, removing debris, and general cleaning.\n**'''Sears Garage Solutions''' Includes garage door sales, install & repair; garage door opener sales, install & repair; flooring, organization and storage products. other services include installation of Entry Doors and emergency repair services.\n**'''ServiceLive''' a wholly-owned subsidiary of Transform Holdco LLC, connects customers with one or more independent contractors for home improvement and repairs.\n*'''Sears Flowers''' (franchised to Teleflora) Website for Flowers, Plants, and gifts available for same-day delivery.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsflowers.com |title=sears Flowers homepage |publisher=www.searsflowers.com |date= |accessdate=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''Sears Driving School''' teaches a state-approved curriculum in Classroom, in-car driving and observation for teens and adults.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.searsdrivingschools.com |title=sears driving school homepage |publisher=https://www.searsdrivingschools.com |date= |accessdate=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''[[Sears Hometown and Outlet Stores]]'''  a subsidiary of Sears that operated a series of more specialized department stores. In 2012, these stores were spun off into an independent company and was reacquired in 2019.<ref name=\"WBBM\">{{cite news|url=https://chicago.cbslocal.com/2019/06/03/sears-parent-co-buying-sears-hometown-and-outlet-stores/|title=Sears Parent Co. Buying Sears Hometown And Outlet Stores|work=[[WBBM-TV]]|publisher=[[CBS Corporation]]|location=[[Chicago]]|date=June 3, 2019|language=en|access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref>\n**'''Sears Hometown Stores''' (formerly known as Sears Authorized Dealer Stores) was formerly part of the retail operation of Sears Holdings and is a small-store (averaging 8,500 square feet) version of Sears full-line department stores. Sears Hometown Stores, established in 1993, is a franchise formula. The stores are usually located away from shopping malls and serve local communities across the United States and [[Puerto Rico]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.emporiagazette.com/news/2009/mar/16/sears_celebrates_new_name/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120731034632/http://www.emporiagazette.com/news/2009/mar/16/sears_celebrates_new_name/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 31, 2012 |title=Sears celebrates new name |date=March 16, 2009 |work=The Emporia Gazette |accessdate=November 25, 2009 |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"The Chicago Tribune\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-10-11/business/chi-sears-gets-446m-from-hometown-and-outlet-spinoff-20121011_1_hometown-and-outlet-sears-hometown-sears-holdings|title=Sears gets $446M from Hometown and Outlet spinoff |date= October 11, 2012|work=The Chicago Tribune |accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref>\n**'''Sears Appliance Outlet''' is an appliance-only version of Sears Outlet. One exists at [[Arizona Mills]] in [[Tempe, Arizona]]; a second Sears Appliance Outlet at [[Great Mall of the Bay Area]] in [[Milpitas, California]] is now a regular Sears Outlet.\n**'''Sears Home Appliance Showrooms''' is a store that offers home appliances and related services in-store. The stores have an internet kiosk where customers are able to view similar products, price match, and order products not available in the store. primarily located in strip malls and centers of metropolitan areas. Averaging 5,000 square feet with a primarily appliance showroom design. These stores carry Kenmore and other national brands of home appliances.\n\n===Former===\n[[File:Closed Sears Hardware.jpg|alt= a closed Sears outlet|thumb|A Sears Hardware in [[Windham, Connecticut|Windham]], [[Connecticut]] which closed in May 2016. Its signage was still intact as of 2017.]]\n*'''Sears Outlet''' is an [[outlet store|outlet]] version of Sears department stores located in various retail locations across the United States. The stores carry new, one-of-a-kind, out of a carton, discontinued, used, scratched and dented merchandise at 20\u201360% off regular retail price. While a wide variety of products are available, appliances make up a large majority of available merchandise. Sears Outlet stores were once known as Sears Surplus. Many former Kmarts have been converted to serve as Sears Outlets, though these often take up less than half the floor space. Each store, on average, is larger than 18,000 square feet in size.<ref name=\"Globes\">{{cite web|url=http://globenewswire.com/news-release/2015/05/26/739192/10135739/en/New-Sears-Outlet-Store-Opens-in-Queens-Village.html|title=New Sears Outlet Store Opens in Queens Village|date=2015-05-26|accessdate=2015-06-03}}</ref><ref name=\"The Chicago Tribune\" /> Sears Outlet was part of Sears' spin-off of its hometown and outlet divisions into a separate company in 2012. Sears Outlet is now owned by [[Franchise Group, Inc]]. as of 2019.\n*'''Sears Appliance & Hardware''' was a chain of [[hardware store]]s that carried the whole line of Sears hardware, and were usually free-standing. At peak, there were more than 110 Sears Appliance & Hardware stores averaging {{convert|28000|sqft|m2}}. Stores were expanded to include Sears' full line of appliances in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/aug/13/business/la-fi-mo-sears-hometown-outlet-hardware-20120813|title=Sears bids Hometown, Outlet, hardware stores goodbye in spinoff |date= August 13, 2012, |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref> Sears Appliance & Hardware was part of Sears' spin-off of its hometown and outlet divisions into a separate company in 2012, and was dissolved in 2019.\n*'''Sears Fashion Outlet''' is 30,000 square feet and carry end-of-season, discontinued and overstock apparel merchandise from both Sears and K-Mart stores in women's, men's, kids, shoes, and accessories product categories as well as home fashions merchandise such as small kitchen appliances, bedding, and bath items. The [[Sugarloaf Mills]] store in [[Lawrenceville, Georgia]] is now a regular Sears Outlet.<ref>{{cite web |title=First Sears fashion outlet to open today at Discover Mills |url=https://www.gwinnettdailypost.com/archive/first-sears-fashion-outlet-to-open-today-at-discover-mills/article_73959388-0b82-5826-9fb5-8a9f0a47b891.html |website=gwinnettdailypost.com |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n*'''[[Lands' End]]''', Sears officially spun off Lands' End in April 2014 amid Sears Holdings's continuing financial distress, including a US$1.4 billion loss in 2013.<ref name=\"Sears Completes Lands' End Spinoff\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/samanthasharf/2014/04/07/sears-completes-lands-end-spinoff/|title=Sears Completes Lands' End Spinoff|date=April 7, 2014|work=Forbes|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> Many Sears domestic full-line locations include a Lands' End \"store within a store\" inside. Sears Holdings, prior to the spin-off, also operated stores that exclusively carry Lands' End clothing and various fashion accessories, footwear, and home goods. These stores, averaging 9,300 square feet, are separate from Sears department stores, usually in outlet malls and regular malls.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/companyProfile?symbol=LE.O \"Profile: Lands' End Inc\"].</ref> Lands' End continues to sell various types of clothing for men, women and children as well as fashion accessories, footwear and home goods<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.landsend.com/aboutus/company/|title=Lands' End {{!}} About Us|website=www.landsend.com|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref> both through its website and an increasing number of stand-alone stores.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investors.landsend.com/news-releases/news-release-details/lands-end-opens-first-standalone-store-new-jersey|title=Lands' End Opens First Standalone Store in New Jersey {{!}} Lands' End, Inc.|website=Lands' End, Inc.|language=en|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref>\n*'''Sears Essentials''' was a chain of discount stores retrofitted from existing Kmart stores. Their product lines were similar to that of Sears Grand stores. In 2006, Sears dropped the brand as it tried to turn Kmart stores into free-standing Sears stores. Most of 50 buildings bearing its name were turned into Sears Grand Stores or reverted to Kmarts.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20060222/NEWS07/200019617/sears-ditches-sears-essentials-name|title=Sears ditches Sears Essentials name |date= February 22, 2006|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[National Tire and Battery]]''' '''(NTB)''' & '''National Tire Warehouse''' '''(NTW)''' is an American brand of auto service centers, spun off by Sears in 2003. Sears created the brand in 1997 by consolidating the Tire America (TA) and National Tire Warehouse (NTW) brands, adding the \"B\" to include its DieHard brand of batteries.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/03/20/business/sears-to-expand-stand-alone-auto-outlets.html \"Sears to Expand Stand-Alone Auto Outlets\"], New York Times, March 20, 1997, </ref> Sears sold the brand, which consisted mostly of stores set apart from its name-brand stores, in 2003 to [[Sumitomo Corporation#Subsidiaries|TBC Corporation]]. A Sears spokesman said \"Because of the separate branding and the lack of proximity to our retail operations, we weren't able to drive growth as a TBC could\".<ref name=\"NYTsale\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/23/business/23SEAR.html \"Sears Plans to Sell National Tire and Battery for $260 Million\"], by Constance L. Hays, New York Times, September 23, 2003, </ref> The chain of 226 stores was reported to have brought in $425 million in revenue and $60 million in profit in 2002.<ref name=\"NYTsale\"/>\n*'''[[Discover Card]]''' Introduced in 1986 as part of the Sears Financial Network, spun off in 1993.\n*'''Sears Brand Central''' was an electronics store. The appliances departments in Sears are now known and referred to internally as Brand Central, although they are not marketed to consumers as such, except for a few locations in Puerto Rico. <!---Note: I cannot find any info on the Brand Central stores online, but I do know they existed. Someone expand this section.--->\n*'''Sears Catalog Sales Stores''' were located in small towns. These stores were very small, even smaller than Sears' current Hometown Dealer stores. At catalog stores, some items could be purchased from the floor, such as appliances; other items could be ordered from catalogs at the store. These stores were often placed in rural markets which were far from full-line Sears stores, allowing for customers to purchase Sears products more easily. These stores were closed in 1993 when Sears closed its catalog business.\n*'''Sears Authorized Catalog Sales Merchant''' was an independent business person who provided many of the same services as the Sears Catalog Sales Store. Similar operations were found in Canada with Sears Canada, as Sears Pickup Locations or Sears Catalogue Sales Merchants.\n*'''Sears Appliance Stores''' were small stores usually between 7,000 and 10,000 square feet.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-sears-shareholder-meeting-0512-biz-20160511-story.html|title= Sears planning smaller-format appliance stores|author= Lauren Zumbach|work= [[Chicago Tribune]]|date= May 11, 2016}}</ref> Sears Appliance Stores displayed and sold (at Retail Store prices) appliances, carpeting, etc. and, in addition, provided a catalog sales department through which catalog items could be ordered. Sears Holdings has opened a Sears Appliances store in Colorado in 2016 with plans to add more throughout the country. By 2019, there were four Sears Appliances Stores in operation, with plans to convert the stores into Sears Home & Life branded stores.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/24/sears-just-opened-a-new-store-heres-what-it-looks-like.html|title=Sears pins its future on small stores selling appliances, mattresses. Here's what that looks like|last=Thomas|first=Lauren|date=2019-05-24|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n*'''Sears Rent-a-Car''' was a car and truck rental chain formed in a mid-1970s joint venture with [[Budget Rent a Car|Budget]]. It was sold to [[Avis Rent a Car System|Avis]] in 2002.\n*'''Sears HomeLife''' was a chain of furniture stores owned by Sears. The concept was introduced at a mall in [[Fresno, California]] in 1989, followed by a stand-alone store in [[Madison, Wisconsin]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3092/is_n19_v28/ai_8091651 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050708081629/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3092/is_n19_v28/ai_8091651 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 8, 2005 |title=A surprisingly new style for Sears: Homelife, Sears' new power furniture format,was unlike anything seen before at the nation's largest retailer |publisher=Findarticles.com |accessdate=July 17, 2009 |year=1989}}</ref> Sears HomeLife averaged 20,000 to 40,000 square feet, featured dark ceilings, theatrical lighting and an expanded array of furniture and accessories. These stores were designed to be much larger than the typical in-store Sears furniture department, which averages around 7,800 square feet. Sears opened Homelife stores as stores-in-a-store to replace the existing furniture departments of their full-line Sears stores. Other Sears HomeLife stores were opened as free-standing locations.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-03-18/business/9001220716_1_sears-earnings-specialty-stores-furniture-and-major-appliances|date=March 18, 1990 |access-date= June 20, 2017|title= Sears Rearranges Furniture With Homelife|author= Wilma Randle and Sharon Stangenes|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Sears sold the stores to Citicorp Venture in 1999, which changed the chain's name to \"HomeLife\". More locations opened, some inside large Sears stores or near the store depending on space availability. HomeLife closed its last stores in 2001.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/stories/2001/07/09/daily29.html |title=HomeLife Furniture closes its doors |publisher=Bizjournals.com |date=July 11, 2001 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref> In Puerto Rico, a few HomeLife locations are still operating.\n*'''Sears Neighborhood''' was a chain similar to Sears Hometown stores, except that Neighborhood stores were located in urban markets. These stores were also independently owned and operated. The concept was introduced in Atlanta in 1998, and another similar store was located in Cincinnati.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://atlanta.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2000/09/18/newscolumn5.html |title=Sears eyeing South DeKalb as site for new urban store |publisher=Atlanta.bizjournals.com |date=September 15, 2000 |accessdate=July 17, 2009 |first=Jarred |last=Schenke}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.enquirer.com/editions/1999/12/22/fin_sears_to_open_urban.html |title=Sears to open urban store |publisher=Enquirer.com |date= |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref> The Neighborhood stores closed in the early 2000s.\n*'''[[The Great Indoors (department store)|The Great Indoors]]''' was a chain of free-standing [[interior design|home decor]] stores that carried high-end home appliances, bedding, and kitchen and bath fixtures. The Great Indoors also offered custom kitchen and bathroom design services. Stores were approximately 140,000 square feet each. Nearly 300 employees were hired for each store.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Sears Holdings|title=California Ready to Discover The Great Indoors|url=https://searsholdings.com/press-releases/pr/1838|accessdate=3 January 2018|date=October 4, 2000|format=Press release}}</ref> While it was a success originally, it succumbed to the housing crash. Sears Holdings announced the closing of all remaining stores in 2012.\n*'''[[Orchard Supply Hardware]]''' was a chain of free-standing hardware stores, spun off by Sears in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |last=Said |first=Carolyn|title=Orchard Supply on its own again |url=http://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Orchard-Supply-on-its-own-again-2439682.php |accessdate=July 20, 2012 |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |date=January 4, 2012}}</ref> The retailer declared bankruptcy and was sold to competitor [[Lowe's|Lowe's Home Improvement]] in June 2013, less than two years after it separated from Sears.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lowes-orchardsupply-idUSBRE95G03J20130617|title=Orchard Supply files for bankruptcy, Lowe's steps in|date=June 17, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=January 16, 2019|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref> On August 22, 2018, Lowe's announced it would cease operations of all Orchard Supply Hardware stores in early 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-osh-closure-20180822-story.html|title=Lowe's closing Orchard Supply Hardware chain it acquired out of bankruptcy|first=James Rufus|last=Koren|website=latimes.com|accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''Sears World Trade, Inc. (Arms and Military Equipment)''' was Sears's troubled import-export unit that catered to the international arms trade chaired by Dep. Sec. of Defense, [[Frank Carlucci]]. It operated from 1982 to 1986. Sears admitted to the effort in December 1986, initially stating they \"only gave the advice in the defense contracting area.\" When the operation ended, the 300-worker unit folded back into the merchandise procurement division.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Day |first1=Kathleen |title=Sears to Close its Ailing World Trade Division |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1986/10/29/sears-to-close-its-ailing-world-trade-division/038d502c-405e-46d4-a02b-2569d2b1ba73/ |work=Washington Post |date=October 29, 1986}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mayer |first1=Caroline |title=Carlucci Supervised Arms Advisers at Sears |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1986/12/11/carlucci-supervised-arms-advisers-at-sears/e042da19-4db2-4ea0-b8f1-b250a4c096ae/ |work=Washington Post |date=December 11, 1986}}</ref>\n*'''Sears Home Alarm''' provides alarm monitoring of new and existing systems, new alarm installations, CCTV systems including camera installations and web-ready DVR recorders, and [[access control]] systems and monitoring, including card-access systems. Available in Canada only.\n*'''Sears Termite & Pest Control''' provided residential and commercial customers with pest control services including termite, mosquito and bed bug treatments, as well as insulation options. was sold to Terminix in 2001.\n*'''Sears Saving Bank''' sold to [[Citigroup|Citicorp]] in 1986<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-01-23-fi-752-story.html|title=Sears Savings Bank Trying to Sell 50 of Its Branch Offices|date=1987-01-23|accessdate=2019-05-03}}</ref>\n*'''[[Western Auto Supply Company]]''' In 1988, Sears purchased Western Auto from Wesray Capital,<ref name=\"suntimes88\"/> which resulted in greater tire selections, and in [[Craftsman tools]] and [[DieHard (type of battery)|DieHard batteries]] being sold at Western Auto stores. In October 1995, Western Auto acquired 84 auto parts stores in Ohio, Indiana, Kentucky, West Virginia and Tennessee from the bankrupted Nationwide Automotive chain for an undisclosed amount<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tirebusiness.com/article/19951016/ISSUE/310169994/western-auto-buys-84-nationwise-stores |title=Western Auto Buys 84 Nationwide Stores |website=Tire Business |date=October 16, 1995 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref> and later acquired Wheels Discount Auto Supply and its 82 auto parts stores in New York and Pennsylvania at the end of the year from [[Fay's Drug]] for $37 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://buffalonews.com/1995/11/06/western-auto-buying-wheels-auto-store-chain/ |title=Western Auto Buying Wheels Auto Store Chain |newspaper=[[Buffalo News]] |date=November 6, 1995 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref><ref name=\"WSJ-1995dec04\">{{cite news |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/djreprints/doc/398596426.html |title=Fay's Completes Sale of Unit |newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]] |date=December 4, 1995 |page=n/a |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url-access=subscription |quote=Fay's Inc. said it completed the sale of its Wheels Discount Auto Supply unit to Sears, Roebuck & Co.'s Western Auto Supply Co. for $37 million. }} [https://search.proquest.com/docview/398596426/ Alternate Link] via [[ProQuest]].</ref> Also during 1995, Sears began to convert the Western Auto stores to the new parts-only Parts America format by eliminating the automotive service bays. By 1998, Sears almost finished converting the 600 remaining company-owned Western Auto stores into Parts America branded stores. By the beginning of 1997, fewer than 850 company-owned stores remained. At that point, the associate stores were the bread and butter of the company, with their more diversified name-brand lines including appliances, electronics, hardware, bicycles, go-karts and outdoor equipment/parts, and their reach into small-town America. Sears removed National Tire Warehouse and Tire America from Western Auto to form a new company called [[National Tire and Battery]],<ref name=\"NYT-1997mar20\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/03/20/business/sears-to-expand-stand-alone-auto-outlets.html |title=Sears to Expand Stand-Alone Auto Outlets |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=March 20, 1997}}</ref> which Sears kept until 2003.<ref name=\"NYT-2003sep23\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/23/business/23SEAR.html |title=Sears Plans to Sell National Tire and Battery for $260 Million |first=Constance L. |last=Hays |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=September 23, 2003}}</ref> After weeks of speculation in 1998, Sears sold the remnants of Western Auto to [[Advance Auto Parts]] of [[Roanoke, Virginia]]. At that point, some associate Western Auto stores owned by dealers became Sears Authorized Dealer Stores.\n*'''[[Dean Witter Reynolds]]''' In 1981, Dean Witter Reynolds was acquired by Sears in a $600 million transaction. Sears' core retail business was facing several challenges, and the company decided to diversify into new businesses, including financial services. Sears, which was already in the financial services business through its ownership of the [[Allstate|Allstate Insurance Company]], announced a major acquisition initiative in financial services.<ref>[http://www.searsarchives.com/history/history1980s.htm Sears History:1980s to today] Accessed: June 8, 2010, </ref> Sears intended for Dean Witter to form the foundation for a larger Sears Financial Services Network that would be available to customers through the company's retail stores.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/07/business/financial-retailing-at-sears.html Financial Retailing at Sears].  New York Times, October 7, 1982, </ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/21/obituaries/21telling.html Edward R. Telling, 86, Dies; Led Sears During Transition]  New York Times, October 21, 2005, </ref>\n*'''[[Coldwell Banker]]''' In 1981 it was bought by Sears, and became part of the Sears Financial Network.<ref name=\"Expansion\">{{cite web |url=http://theplayatimes.com/2015/04/16/7365/ |date=April 16, 2015 |title=A Brief History of Coldwell Banker |publisher=The Playa Times |accessdate=October 22, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525102617/http://theplayatimes.com/2015/04/16/7365/ |archive-date=2015-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author= Robert J. Cole |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/10/09/business/sears-will-purchase-dean-witter-in-plan-to-offer-financial-services.html |date=October 9, 1981 |title=Sears Will Purchase Dean Witter In Plan To Offer Financial Services |newspaper=New York Times |accessdate=October 22, 2015}}</ref> Sears sold the residential real estate division to the Fremont Group, a California investment company, for $230 million in 1993.<ref>{{cite news|author= James S. Granelli  |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-10-06/business/fi-42893_1_fremont-group |date=October 6, 1993 |title=Sears Completes Sale of Coldwell to Fremont Group |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=October 22, 2015}}</ref> Sears sold Coldwell's commercial real-estate operations to a management-led buyout in April 1989, renamed [[CBRE Group|CB Commercial Holdings Inc]] and based in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1993-05-14-mn-35355-story.html|title=Sears Selling O.C.-Based Coldwell Unit|website=latimes.com|accessdate=May 3, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''[[Allstate Insurance Company]]''' Named after Sears\u2019 tire brand, Allstate went into business on April 17, 1931, offering auto insurance by direct mail and through the Sears catalog.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia\">{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/The_Allstate_Corp.aspx|title=Encyclopedia- Allstate Corp.|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia.com|accessdate=2011-02-23|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628234217/http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/The_Allstate_Corp.aspx|archivedate=2011-06-28}}</ref><ref>\u201cArnstein & Lehr, The First 120 Years\u201d, (Louis A. Lehr, Jr.)(Amazon), p. 26</ref> In 1993, Allstate went public when Sears sold 19.8% of the company.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-06-03/business/9306030069_1_concurrent-international-offering-allstate-sears|title=Allstate Initial Offering Priced At The Top|work=tribunedigital-chicagotribune|access-date=2017-12-08|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209044451/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-06-03/business/9306030069_1_concurrent-international-offering-allstate-sears|archivedate=2017-12-09}}</ref>  At the time, it was the largest IPO to date.\n*'''Sears Optical''' Provided Comprehensive Vision Exam, Pediatric Vision Exam, Contact Lenses (including astigmatism and bifocal contact lenses), Diagnostic and Medical Treatment of Eye Diseases, Urgent Care, Cataract and Glaucoma Surgery Consultation/referrals, Low Vision Treatment, Advanced Testing Instruments, and Eyeglass Dispensary services. Sears Optical is operated by Luxottica, which terminated their relationship with Sears and closed all remaining Sears Optical locations in February 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.visionmonday.com/latest-news/article/luxottica-retail-to-terminate-relationship-with-sears-and-close-all-remaining-sears-optical-locations-by-february-2020/|title=Luxottica Retail to Terminate Relationship With Sears and Close All Remaining Sears Optical Locations by February 2020|last=|first=|date=|work=Vision Monday|access-date=3 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Copy edit-inline|for=capitalization|date=February 2020}}\n\n===Exclusive brands (current)===\nSince [[Sears Holdings#Founding|the merger of Sears & Kmart in 2005]], many brands are now shared by both stores.\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|rules=yes|\n*[[Adam Levine#Business ventures and endorsements|Adam Levine]] Collection \u2013 Men's and women's clothing\n*Athletech \u2013 Athletic clothing and shoes<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.trademarkia.com/athletech-78801436.html |title=Athletech Trademark Information |publisher=LegalForce, Inc |date=June 9, 2017 |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n*Basic Editions \u2013 Men's, women's and children's clothing\n*Cannon \u2013 Bed and bath\n*Canyon River Blues \u2013 Men's and women's clothing (a children's sub-brand called CRB Kids also exists)\n*Cat & Co \u2013 Cat supplies\n*Champion Breed \u2013 Dog supplies\n*Colormate \u2013 Bedding and bath accessories<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.trademarkia.com/colormate-77056410.html |title=Colormate Trademark Information |publisher=LegalForce, Inc |date=August 3, 2017 |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n*Covington \u2013 Men's and women's dresswear.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.trademarkia.com/covington-78088021.html |title=Covington Trademark Information |publisher=LegalForce, Inc |date=December 14, 2013 |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[DieHard (brand)|DieHard]] \u2013 Batteries, clothing, and work shoes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/diehard.htm |title=DieHard: 1967\u2013present |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*Easy Living \u2013 Painting equipment\n*Essential Home \u2013 Bed, bath, and kitchen supplies\n*[[Everlast (boxing)|Everlast]] \u2013 Men's, women's, and children's athletic apparel and footwear; through a license deal<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chainstoreage.com/article/sears-holdings-signs-licensing-deal-everlast/ |title=Sears Holdings signs licensing deal with Everlast |publisher=Chain Store Age |date=December 12, 2010 |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n*Evolv \u2013 Tools\n*[[Joe Boxer]] \u2013 Men's and women's underwear and sleepwear\n*[[Kenmore (brand)|Kenmore]] \u2013 Appliances, grills, vacuums (Sears brand also sold in other stores)\n*Laura Scott \u2013 Women's clothing<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.trademarkia.com/laura-scott-77871268.html |title=Laura Scott Trademark Information |publisher=LegalForce, Inc |date=September 11, 2012 |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n*Metaphor \u2013 Women's clothing\n*Northwest Territory \u2013 Men's and women's clothing and camping gear<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.trademarkia.com/northwest-territory-85932526.html |title=Northwest territory Trademark Information |publisher=LegalForce, Inc |date=February 9, 2016 |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n*Outdoor Life \u2013 More rugged men's and women's clothing.\n*R1893 \u2013 Women's clothing, primarily jeans\n*Roebuck & Co. \u2013 Men's, women's, and children's clothing and shoes\n*Roebucks \u2013 Formerly clothing, now used for men's work shoes<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/roebucks.htm |title=Roebucks: 1949\u2013present |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*Simply Emma \u2013 Women's clothing and jewelry<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.trademarkia.com/simply-emma-86849562.html |title=Simply Emma Trademark Information |publisher=LegalForce, Inc |date=October 4, 2017 |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n*Simply Styled \u2013 Men's, women's, and children's clothing and shoes<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.trademarkia.com/simply-styled-86849574.html |title=Simply Styled Trademark Information |publisher=LegalForce, Inc |date=December 20, 2016 |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n*Smart Sense \u2013 Groceries, health, and household\n*Structure \u2013 Men's clothing and shoes (originally owned by [[Express, Inc.]] before Sears bought it in 2003)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://searsholdings.com/press-releases/pr/1381 |title=Sears Acquires Structure Brand from Limited Brands |publisher=Sears Holdings |date=September 15, 2003 |accessdate=November 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.trademarkia.com/structure-85924102.html |title=Structure Trademark Information |publisher=LegalForce, Inc |date=February 19, 2015 |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Thom McAn]] \u2013 Shoes\n*[[Toughskins]] \u2013 Children's clothing<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/toughskins.htm |title=Toughskins: 1971\u2013present |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*Weatherbeater \u2013 Painting equipment\n}}\n\n===Exclusive brands (former)===\n[[File:Sears Tower 127 Film.jpg|thumb|Sears Tower Brand 127 Film (Expired: November 1963)]]\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n*Allen \u2013 Washing machines\n*[[Allstate]] \u2013 Automobiles, motorcycles and mopeds, vehicle parts, insurance<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/allstate.htm |title=Allstate: 1926\u20131995 (Sears' divestment) |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*Alphaline \u2013 Electronics accessories, cables, headphones (video on-demand service powered by Roxio under the same name launched in 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/12/28/sears-kmart-launch-alphaline-entertainment-movie-download-servi/ |title=Sears, Kmart launch Alphaline Entertainment movie download service |publisher=[[Oath Tech Network]] [[AOL Tech]] |date=December 28, 2010 |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref> abandoned in 2015)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trademarkia.com/alphaline-85050437.html |title=ALPHALINE Trademark Information |publisher=LegalForce, Inc. |date=February 2, 2015 |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n*Amanda Stewart - Women's clothing and accessories\n*[[Celestial Star]] \u2013 Diamond jewelry\n*[[Challenge Records (1920s)|Challenge Records]] \u2013 Record Label\n*[[Cheryl Tiegs]] \u2013 Clothing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/cheryltiegs.htm |title=Cheryl Tiegs: 1981\u20131989 |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*[[Kenmore Appliances|Coldspot]] \u2013 Appliances<ref>{{cite web|title=Coldspot: 1928\u20131976|url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/coldspot.htm|work=Sears Archives|publisher=Sears Brands|accessdate=31 July 2011}}</ref>\n*Companion \u2013 Tools\n*[[Conqueror Records]] \u2013 Record Label\n*[[Craftsman (tools)|Craftsman]] \u2013 Tools (sold to [[Stanley Black and Decker]]; still sold in Sears and other stores, under licensing deals, but no longer an exclusive brand)\n*Dashmate \u2013 Automobile radios and tape players\n*[[David Bradley (plowman)|David Bradley]] \u2013 Farm machinery and equipment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/davidbradley.htm |title=David Bradley: 1910\u20131966 |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*[[Dean Witter Reynolds]] \u2013 Financial services\n*Dunlap \u2013 Tools\n*Economy \u2013 Iceboxes, fountain pens, sewing machine cabinets, gasoline engines, portable saw rigs, farm equipment, cream separators<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/economy.htm|title=Economy: 1902-1947|website=www.searsarchives.com}}</ref>\n*Free Spirit \u2013 Bicycles\n*Gold Bond \u2013 Footwear\n*Goolagong \u2013 Clothing\n*Handiman \u2013 Line of tractors and walk-behind equipment<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.farmcollector.com/tractors/sears-handiman-zmlz16marzhur |title=Rediscovering the Sears Handiman Line \u2013 Tractors |last=Moore |first=Sam |date=March 2016 |website=Farm Collector |language=en |access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref>\n*Harmony House \u2013 Interior decorating products<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/harmonyhouse.htm |title=Harmony House: 1940\u20131968 |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*Hearthside \u2013 Rug looms and quilting frames\n*Hercules \u2013 Work clothing, appliances, insurance, sewage systems, [[letter jackets]], fire extinguishers, heavy-duty coveralls, home heating systems<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/hercules.htm |title=Hercules: 1908\u20131965 |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*Hillary \u2013 Camping and outdoor gear\n*Homart \u2013 Heating and cooling systems, plumbing supplies, electrical supplies, kitchen cabinets, building supplies\n*[[J. C. Higgins]] \u2013 Sporting goods, camping<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/jchiggins.htm |title=J.C. Higgins: 1908\u20131964 |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*Kromedge \u2013 Sawblades, dadoes, moldering heads, router bits\n*LXI \u2013 Stereo audio components and systems\n*[[Oxford Records]] \u2013 Record Label\n*Penske \u2013 Automotive testing tools\n*Permanex \u2013 Blow-molded polyethylene tool storage cases, gas cans\n*Personal Identity - teen clothing and footwear\n*Pilgrim \u2013 Clothing<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/pilgrim.htm |title=Pilgrim: 1905\u20131964 |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*PROformance \u2013 Stereo audio components and systems (replaced LXI)\n*Sears Video Arcade \u2013 In-house version of [[Atari]] in the early 1980s (discontinued in favor of the actual Atari systems)\n*Seventeen \u2013 Young women's clothing (part of a 2014 license deal with [[Seventeen (American magazine)|the magazine of the same name]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hearst.com/newsroom/seventeen-launches-new-clothing-line-with-sears |title=Seventeen Launches New Clothing Line with Sears |publisher=Hearst Corporation |date=August 26, 2014 |accessdate=November 5, 2017}}</ref>\n*Silvertone \u2013 Stereos, televisions, musical instruments<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searsarchives.com/brands/silvertone.htm |title=Silvertone: 1915\u20131972 |publisher=Searsarchives.com |date=October 31, 2006 |accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n*[[Silvertone Records (1916)|Silvertone Records]] \u2013 Record Label\n*[[Supertone Records]] \u2013 Record Label\n*Ted Williams Brand \u2013 Sporting goods\n*Tower \u2013 Cameras, photo supplies, office equipment\n}}\n\n===Sponsorships===\nThe company sponsors, through the Sears Auto Centers, the Formula Drift Darren McNamara Sears/Falken Saturn Sky drift car. It sponsored the [[NASCAR]] [[Camping World Truck Series|Truck Series]], using the Craftsman brand as the title sponsor, from the series' inception in the [[1995 NASCAR SuperTruck Series presented by Craftsman]] to the [[2008 NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series|2008 season]], when the agreement ended.<ref>[http://www.kansascity.com/news/breaking_news/story/388059.html \"Craftsman Dropping Sponsorship of NASCAR Truck Series\"]. ''[[The Kansas City Star]]''. December 4, 2007.</ref> Craftsman tools remain the official tools of NASCAR. The company sponsored the television series ''[[Extreme Makeover: Home Edition]]''. It sponsors and currently has naming rights to the [[Sears Centre]], an 11,000-seat multi-purpose family entertainment, cultural and sports center, constructed in 2006 in Hoffman Estates. The company also underwrote the [[PBS]] television series ''[[Mister Rogers' Neighborhood]]'', under the name The Sears-Roebuck Foundation from the show's premiere in 1968 until 1992. It sponsored the #10 [[Gillett Evernham Motorsports]] car of Scott Riggs for the September 2, 2007, running of the [[Sharp AQUOS 500]] at [[California Speedway]] through its Sears Auto Center branch. However, Riggs failed to qualify for the event.\nIn 2016, Craftsman became the title sponsor of the World Racing Group, World of Outlaws Sprint car racing series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woosprint.com/sponsors|title=World of Outlaws Craftsman Sprint Car Series \u2013 Sponsors|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Employee relations==\n[[File:Sears Centro Historico.jpg|thumb|Sears building in the [[Edificio La Nacional]] building in Mexico City, across from the [[Palacio de Bellas Artes]].]]\nSears has struggled with employee relations. One notable example was the shift in 1992 from an hourly wage based on longevity to a base wage (usually between US$3.50 and US$6 per hour) and commissions ranging from 0.5% to 11%. Sears claimed the new base wage, often constituting a substantial (up to 40%) cut in pay, was done \"to be successful in this highly competitive environment\".<ref>\"600-plus Sears jobs to be cut\", ''Chicago Tribune'', February 13, 1992</ref>\n\nIn early October 2007, Sears cut commission rates for employees in select departments to anywhere from 0.5% to 4% but equalized the base wage across all Home Improvement and Electronics departments. In 2011, commission rates on non-base items were cut by 2% in the electronics department. In late 2009, the commission on sales of \"base items\" from the electronic department was cut to 1%. As of 2017, appliances is the only remaining department where compensation is based entirely on commission. Other departments give a base pay plus commission. In many stores, jewelry department associates receive a low base salary with 1% commission on their sales.\n\nIn March 2019, Sears claimed that it was ending life insurance benefits for an undisclosed number of its 90,000 retirees. A few months earlier the company handed out over $25 million in bonuses to executives.<ref>{{cite news |last= Folley|first=Aris|date=March 30, 2019|title=Sears cutting life insurance benefits for up to 90,000 retirees: report|url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/436593-sears-cuts-life-insurance-benefits-for-up-to-90000-retirees|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|location= |access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref> This key Sears Retiree Benefit was worth between $5,000 and $15,000 for most of the pool (29,000) of eligible retired employees.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mooney|first=John|date=July 30, 2019|title=Sears Retiree Benefit|url=https://choiceseniorlife.com/2019/07/what-do-you-do-when-sears-cancels-your-life-insurance-policy/ |website=ChoiceSeniorLife.com}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2019, former Sears Holdings chairman and CEO Eddie Lampert, months after purchasing the remains of Sears from the holding company, threatened not to pay out the $43 million in pension payments<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/29/business/sears-severance/index.html|title=Sears' owner wants to get out of paying $43 million in severance to former employees|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref> owed to 90,000 former Sears and Kmart employees and retirees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/government-fears-eddie-lampert-would-wipe-out-sears-pension-plans|title=Government fears Eddie Lampert would wipe out Sears' pension plans|last=|first=|date=February 1, 2019|work=|access-date=}}</ref> A ''[[Forbes]]'' editorial pointed out that [[Steven Mnuchin]], [[Secretary of the Treasury]], was a board member of Sears Holding until 2016, and is presently one of three directors of the [[Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation]], which manages administration of pensions for defunct or bankrupt businesses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/warrenshoulberg/2019/06/03/the-shameless-sears-world-of-eddie-lampert-continues/#296430171fd6/|title=The Shameless Sears World Of Eddie Lampert Continues|last=|first=|date=June 3, 2019|work=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"50\">\nFile:Sears, Robuck & Co. letterhead 1907.jpg|Letterhead logo 1907\nFile:Sears logo 1966-1984.svg|Logo 1963\u201384\nFile:Sears1984.png|1984\u201394\nFile:Sears logo 1994-2004.svg|1994\u20132004 (still used in [[Sears Mexico|Mexico]])\nFile:SearsLogo.svg|2004\u201310 (2004\u201316 in Canada)\nFile:Sears logo 2010-present.svg|2010\u201320\n</gallery>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile: Sears Auto Center.jpg|Sears Auto Center at [[Steeplegate Mall]] in [[Concord, New Hampshire]]. Both the Auto Center and the main Sears store at this location closed in February 2020.\nFile:2006 Sears Hawthorn Center.jpg|Exterior of the Sears at the [[Westfield Hawthorn]] in [[Vernon Hills, Illinois]]. This location closed in August 2018.\nFile:1.8.09ParamusParkMallByLuigiNovi3.jpg|Mall entrance to the former Sears at [[Paramus Park]] in [[Paramus, New Jersey]].\nFile:Searsessentials.jpg|Exterior of the Sears Essentials in [[Palm Springs, Florida]] (reopened as Sears Outlet and closed)\nFile: Sears grand tarentum.JPG|2013 photo of the mall entrance to the Sears Grand at [[Pittsburgh Mills]] in [[Tarentum, Pennsylvania]]. This Sears closed in January 2015.\nFile: Sears Parts Repair Brooklyn.JPG|Exterior of the Sears Parts & Repair Store in [[Brooklyn, Ohio]]\nFile: Sears Ciudad de Mexico.jpg|Exterior of the Sears in [[Mexico City]].\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Chicago|Illinois|Companies}}\n*[[Gala-Sears]] \u2013 defunct Chilean unit\n*[[Sears Canada]] \u2013 defunct Canadian unit\n*[[Sears (Mexico)]] \u2013 Mexican unit held by [[Grupo Carso]]\n*[[Sears plc]] \u2013 former UK company unrelated to U.S. retailer\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*Chang, Myong-Hun, and Joseph E. Harrington Jr. \"Organizational structure and firm innovation in a retail chain.\" ''Computational & Mathematical Organization Theory'' 3.4 (1998): 267\u2013288. compares