hip}}\n\n[[Category:African handball championships]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions hosted by Algeria|Handball]]\n[[Category:1989 in handball|A]]\n[[Category:1989 in Algerian sport|Handball]]\n[[Category:Handball in Algeria]]\n[[Category:20th century in Algiers]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Algeria]]\n[[Category:July 1989 sports events in Africa]]\n", "name_user": "Frietjes", "label": "safe", "comment": "expand templates perFb team TfD outcomeandFb competition TfD outcomeandFb cl TfD outcomeandFb rbr TfD outcome", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1989_African_Men%27s_Handball_Championship"}
{"title_page": "Lekan Babalola", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian jazz percussionist and musician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Lekan Babalola\n| image         = \n| alt           =\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Olalekan Babalola\n| \n| birth_place   = [[Lagos State]], Nigeria \nMay 15, 1960\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = Nigerian, British\n| other_names   =\n| alma_mater     = {{plainlist|\n*[[Chelsea College of Aeronautical and Automobile Engineering]]\n*[[Saint Martin's School of Art]]}}\n| known_for     =\n| spouse        = Kate Luxmoore\n| children        = 5 \n| notable_works =\n| website             = \n| module     = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background   = solo_singer\n| origin              = \n| genre               = [[Afrobeat]], [[jazz]]\n| instrument          = Vocals, [[conga]], [[Bongo drum]]\n| years_active        = 1983\u2013present\n| label               = \n| occupation    = musician, percussionist\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n*[[Fela Kuti]]\n*[[Ali Farka Tour\u00e9]]\n*[[Cassandra Wilson]]}}\n| notable_instruments = \n}}}}\n\n'''Olalekan Babalola''' (born {{circa|1960}}) is a Nigerian [[List of jazz percussionists|jazz percussionist]] and musician. Born in [[Lagos State]], [[Nigeria]] where he began playing the [[conga]] at a young age, he has released seven albums and jointly won two [[Grammy Award]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/29/west-africa-afrobeat-uprising-musicians-afropop-big-band-political-spirit|title=Afrobeat uprising: the musicians fighting against a tide of sugary pop|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Mark|first=Monica|location=[[Lagos]]|date=29 July 2014|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBabalola was born in Lagos State, South-Western Nigeria where he attended Bishop Oluwole Primary School, Agege for his basic education before proceeding to [[Iwo, Osun|Iwo]] in the old [[Oyo State]] for his secondary school education. At the age of six, he had started playing the conga at his father's Aladura church and later formed a patchwork band with his peers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thenet.ng/2016/10/nigerias-1st-grammy-award-winner/|title=Meet Lekan Babalola, Nigeria's 1st Grammy Award winner|work=Nigerian Entertainment Today|last=Taiwo|first=Jide|date=13 October 2016|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, he left Nigeria for the United Kingdom to study automobile engineering at the [[Chelsea College of Aeronautical and Automobile Engineering]] after he won a Lagos State Scholarship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/videos/world/2016/10/07/african-voices-music-masters-spc-b.cnn#|title=Musician Lekan Babalola: I love freedom of expression|work=[[CNN]]|last=|first=|date=7 October 2016|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref> Babalola however dropped the engineering programme for music and later enrolled at the [[Saint Martin's School of Art|Central Saint Martin's College of Art and Design]] where he studied filmmaking. He proceeded to the [[Northern Film School]] where he completed his master's degree.<ref name=\"all\">{{cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201505042105.html|title=Nigeria: Lekan Babalola \u2013 Lord of the Drums|work=[[Thisday|THISDAY Live]]|last=Olatunbosun|first=Yinka|publisher=[[allAfrica]]|date=3 May 2005|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe began his professional career after joining a band called Samba Samba Band and later New York City-based Art Blakey's Jazz Messengers band, where he perfected playing the Bongo drums and performing jazz music. Upon his return to the U.K, Babalola later went on to work with notable acts including [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Ernest Ranglin]], [[Branford Marsalis]], African Jazz All Stars, [[Roy Ayers]], [[David Byrne]], Damon Albarn, [[Tony Allen (musician)|Tony Allen]] amongst others.<ref name=\"all\"/> In 2006, he became Nigeria's first [[Grammy Award]] winner for his work on [[Ali Farka Tour\u00e9]]'s ''In the Heart of the Moon'' which he was credited in three tracks. He also won a second Grammy in 2009 for his work on [[Cassandra Wilson]]'s 2008 album titled ''[[Loverly]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thenet.ng/2016/10/nigerian-grammy-winner-lekan/|title=Hiding in plain sight: The story of Lekan Babalola, Nigeria\u2019s 1st Grammy Award winner|work=[[Nigerian Entertainment Today]]|last=Taiwo|first=Jide|date=12 October 2016|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Inc.2008\">{{cite book|author=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|title=Billboard|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DhMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA46|date=14 June 2008|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|pages=46\u2013|id=|ISSN=0006-2510}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs artist|291027-Lekan-Babalola|Lekan Babalola}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Babalola, Lekan}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Yoruba musicians]]\n[[Category:Jazz percussionists]]\n[[Category:Nigerian jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Lagos State]]\n[[Category:Atomic Bomb! Band members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nigerian jazz percussionist and musician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Lekan Babalola\n| image         = \n| alt           =\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Olalekan Babalola\n| \n| birth_place   = [[Lagos State]], Nigeria \nMay 15,1960\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = Nigerian, British\n| other_names   =\n| alma_mater     = {{plainlist|\n*[[Chelsea College of Aeronautical and Automobile Engineering]]\n*[[Saint Martin's School of Art]]}}\n| known_for     =\n| spouse        = Kate Luxmoore\n| children        = 5 \n| notable_works =\n| website             = \n| module     = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background   = solo_singer\n| origin              = \n| genre               = [[Afrobeat]], [[jazz]]\n| instrument          = Vocals, [[conga]], [[Bongo drum]]\n| years_active        = 1983\u2013present\n| label               = \n| occupation    = musician, percussionist\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n*[[Fela Kuti]]\n*[[Ali Farka Tour\u00e9]]\n*[[Cassandra Wilson]]}}\n| notable_instruments = \n}}}}\n\n'''Olalekan Babalola''' (born {{circa|1960}}) is a Nigerian [[List of jazz percussionists|jazz percussionist]] and musician. Born in [[Lagos State]], [[Nigeria]] where he began playing the [[conga]] at a young age, he has released seven albums and jointly won two [[Grammy Award]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/29/west-africa-afrobeat-uprising-musicians-afropop-big-band-political-spirit|title=Afrobeat uprising: the musicians fighting against a tide of sugary pop|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Mark|first=Monica|location=[[Lagos]]|date=29 July 2014|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBabalola was born in Lagos State, South-Western Nigeria where he attended Bishop Oluwole Primary School, Agege for his basic education before proceeding to [[Iwo, Osun|Iwo]] in the old [[Oyo State]] for his secondary school education. At the age of six, he had started playing the conga at his father's Aladura church and later formed a patchwork band with his peers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thenet.ng/2016/10/nigerias-1st-grammy-award-winner/|title=Meet Lekan Babalola, Nigeria's 1st Grammy Award winner|work=Nigerian Entertainment Today|last=Taiwo|first=Jide|date=13 October 2016|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, he left Nigeria for the United Kingdom to study automobile engineering at the [[Chelsea College of Aeronautical and Automobile Engineering]] after he won a Lagos State Scholarship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/videos/world/2016/10/07/african-voices-music-masters-spc-b.cnn#|title=Musician Lekan Babalola: I love freedom of expression|work=[[CNN]]|last=|first=|date=7 October 2016|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref> Babalola however dropped the engineering programme for music and later enrolled at the [[Saint Martin's School of Art|Central Saint Martin's College of Art and Design]] where he studied filmmaking. He proceeded to the [[Northern Film School]] where he completed his master's degree.<ref name=\"all\">{{cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201505042105.html|title=Nigeria: Lekan Babalola \u2013 Lord of the Drums|work=[[Thisday|THISDAY Live]]|last=Olatunbosun|first=Yinka|publisher=[[allAfrica]]|date=3 May 2005|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe began his professional career after joining a band called Samba Samba Band and later New York City-based Art Blakey's Jazz Messengers band, where he perfected playing the Bongo drums and performing jazz music. Upon his return to the U.K, Babalola later went on to work with notable acts including [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Ernest Ranglin]], [[Branford Marsalis]], African Jazz All Stars, [[Roy Ayers]], [[David Byrne]], Damon Albarn, [[Tony Allen (musician)|Tony Allen]] amongst others.<ref name=\"all\"/> In 2006, he became Nigeria's first [[Grammy Award]] winner for his work on [[Ali Farka Tour\u00e9]]'s ''In the Heart of the Moon'' which he was credited in three tracks. He also won a second Grammy in 2009 for his work on [[Cassandra Wilson]]'s 2008 album titled ''[[Loverly]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thenet.ng/2016/10/nigerian-grammy-winner-lekan/|title=Hiding in plain sight: The story of Lekan Babalola, Nigeria\u2019s 1st Grammy Award winner|work=[[Nigerian Entertainment Today]]|last=Taiwo|first=Jide|date=12 October 2016|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Inc.2008\">{{cite book|author=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|title=Billboard|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DhMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA46|date=14 June 2008|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|pages=46\u2013|id=|ISSN=0006-2510}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs artist|291027-Lekan-Babalola|Lekan Babalola}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Babalola, Lekan}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Yoruba musicians]]\n[[Category:Jazz percussionists]]\n[[Category:Nigerian jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Lagos State]]\n[[Category:Atomic Bomb! Band members]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lekan_Babalola"}
{"title_page": "Lee Gaines", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Lee Gaines\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = File:Lee Gaines.JPG\n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = Otho Lee Gaines\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = April 21, 1914\n| birth_place      = \n| origin           = \n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1987|07|15|1914|04|21}} \n| death_place      = \n| genre            = \n| occupation       = Jazz musician \n| instrument       = \n| years_active     = <!-- YYYY\u2013YYYY (or \u2013present) -->\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Ella Fitzgerald]], [[Count Basie]], [[Jimmy Lunceford]], [[Charlie Barnet]], [[Fred Astaire]], [[Ruth Brown]], [[Les Paul]]\n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} or {{Official URL}} -->\n| module           = \n| module2          = \n| module3          = \n}}\n\n'''Otho Lee Gaines''' (April 21, 1914 - July 15, 1987) was an American jazz singer and lyricist.<ref name=\"NYTObit\">{{cite news|title=Lee Gaines, 73, a jazz singer|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/07/21/obituaries/lee-gaines-73-a-jazz-singer.html}}</ref> Gaines wrote the lyrics for \"[[Take the \"A\" Train]]\" and \"[[Just A-Sittin' and A-Rockin']]\", two [[jazz standards]] by [[Billy Strayhorn]].<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/>\n\nLee Gaines was from [[Chickasaw County, Mississippi|Buena Vista]], in Mississippi, and began singing as a bass in high school, he formed a vocal quartet at [[Langston University]] in 1933, and returned to the United States in 1937 having toured South America.<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/> Gaines was a founding member of the [[Delta Rhythm Boys]] who achieved their peak popularity in the 1940s and 50's, having recorded with [[Ella Fitzgerald]], [[Count Basie]], [[Jimmy Lunceford]], [[Charlie Barnet]], [[Fred Astaire]], [[Ruth Brown]] and [[Les Paul]].<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/>\n\nThe Delta Rhythm Boys moved to Europe in the 1950s. Gaines had lived in Finland for a year at the time of his death from cancer in 1987 and he is buried in Maunulan uurnalehto at Helsinki (Section 39, lot 109). Gaines was married to Muriel Gaines, a calypso singer and former [[Cotton Club]] dancer.<ref name=\"Company1952\">{{cite book|author=Johnson Publishing Company|title=Jet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SEMDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA61|accessdate=20 January 2013|date=29 May 1952|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|pages=61\u2013|issn=0021-5996}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gaines, Lee}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:American lyricists]]\n[[Category:American jazz singers]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Finland]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Langston University alumni]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:People from Chickasaw County, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Singers from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Mississippi]]\n\n\n{{US-jazz-singer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Lee Gaines\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = File:Lee Gaines.JPG\n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = Otho Lee Gaines\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = April 21, 1914\n| birth_place      = \n| origin           = \n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1987|07|15|1914|04|21}} \n| death_place      = \n| genre            = \n| occupation       = Jazz musician \n| instrument       = \n| years_active     = <!-- YYYY\u2013YYYY (or \u2013present) -->\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Ella Fitzgerald]], [[Count Basie]], [[Jimmy Lunceford]], [[Charlie Barnet]], [[Fred Astaire]], [[Ruth Brown]], [[Les Paul]]\n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} or {{Official URL}} -->\n| module           = \n| module2          = \n| module3          = \n}}\n\n'''Otho Lee Gaines''' (April 21, 1914 - July 15, 1987) was an American jazz singer and lyricist.<ref name=\"NYTObit\">{{cite news|title=Lee Gaines, 73, a jazz singer|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/07/21/obituaries/lee-gaines-73-a-jazz-singer.html}}</ref> Gaines wrote the lyrics for \"[[Take the \"A\" Train]]\" and \"[[Just A-Sittin' and A-Rockin']]\", two [[jazz standards]] by [[Billy Strayhorn]].<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/>\n\nLee Gaines was from [[Chickasaw County, Mississippi|Buena Vista]], in Mississippi, and began singing as a bass in high school, he formed a vocal quartet at [[Langston University]] in 1933, and returned to the United States in 1937 having toured South America.<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/> Gaines was a founding member of the [[Delta Rhythm Boys]] who achieved their peak popularity in the 1940s and 50's, having recorded with [[Ella Fitzgerald]], [[Count Basie]], [[Jimmy Lunceford]], [[Charlie Barnet]], [[Fred Astaire]], [[Ruth Brown]] and [[Les Paul]].<ref name=\"NYTObit\"/>\n\nThe Delta Rhythm Boys moved to Europe in the 1950s. Gaines had lived in Finland for a year at the time of his death from cancer in 1987 and he is buried in Maunulan uurnalehto at Helsinki (Section 39, lot 109). Gaines was married to Muriel Gaines, a calypso singer and former [[Cotton Club]] dancer.<ref name=\"Company1952\">{{cite book|author=Johnson Publishing Company|title=Jet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SEMDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA61|accessdate=20 January 2013|date=29 May 1952|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|pages=61\u2013|issn=0021-5996}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gaines, Lee}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:American lyricists]]\n[[Category:American jazz singers]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Finland]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Langston University alumni]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:People from Chickasaw County, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Singers from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Mississippi]]\n\n\n{{US-jazz-singer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Gaines"}
